commit_message:
Image corruption should not fail with not enough hosts available

We should catch ProcessExecution errors and fail them instead of
trying to retry scheduling these requests. They would just fail
again. Also, the proper error message is not sent back to the
user and they won't know the real problem until someone looks
in the logs. We've seen this in the gate as well (bug 1303802).

Closes-Bug: #1436166
Change-Id: I644d69443b4a5c72c9cae233413e711f1f88d0e3

commit_message:
Fix for installing rally to multiple virtual environments

Changes:
  - Added flags for manually specifying rally installation and config path
  - Added mandatory flag to allow force overwrite of existing rally installation.
  - Checks for existing installation and if specified venv is in use.

Change-Id: I3e6240b167de057d89ddd09c9dc8558cd3cde7f1
Closes-Bug: #1413105

commit_message:
set default auth_strategy to keystone

Like in change Ife63dc7ab680fcf0588d95c98fc9f29901485c64 for Nova
the default for auth_strategy should be keystone instead of noauth.

DocImpact Changed default config option 'auth_strategy' to 'keystone'.

Change-Id: Ia72c5bf9be641b438a4d428ba43e501d1aa333d6
Closes-Bug: #1327503

Run keystoneclient functional tests on master only

The stable/juno branch doesn't have a 'functional' tox target, so
all reviews are currently failing this job.

commit_message:
instance termination with update_dns_entries set fails

In If9554a2e98397c5e63e929e1606d99dd2328262c, changed the "fixed_ips"
array to contain a list of string ip address, rather than fixed_ip
objects, but neglected to update the code under the
CONF.update_dns_entries branch below to match. We need to
build a list of unique network ids for update_dns_entries.

Closes-Bug: #1427295
Change-Id: I60e9148d1120d308d33d48a67912a595a3353d67

request.

address None." in successful gate runs because with the Tempest change
the network uuid is passed in (if available) on the boot request but
there is no address provided, e.g.:

Body: {"server": {"imageRef": "328dba0f-f13b-47eb-bfce-6e3f6ab07eaa",
"return_reservation_id": true, "flavorRef": "42", "name":

"cf357903-a60c-4b1c-8524-a0aaa4bb2fe7"}], "max_count": 2}}

When deleting an instance before it's completely built, we try to
deallocate the network and that failed since deallocate_for_instance
wasn't filtering out None addresses from requested_networks.

This fixes the problem by simply filtering the list of fixed IPs from
requested_networks before trying to deallocate the fixed IPs.

Closes-Bug: #1439302

Change-Id: I459a98151406a0b125a65b00fa0186eb5df97b1c

commit_message:
Filter fixed IPs from requested_networks in deallocate_for_instance

With nova-network, the fixed IP address is optional on the server create
request.

Tempest commit 9ce97dfa353e3659aa0ec0a7f62ed3a7e54c4bdf merged on 3/26
and we started seeing "FixedIpNotFoundForAddress: Fixed ip not found for
address None." in successful gate runs because with the Tempest change
the network uuid is passed in (if available) on the boot request but
there is no address provided, e.g.:

Body: {"server": {"imageRef": "328dba0f-f13b-47eb-bfce-6e3f6ab07eaa",
"return_reservation_id": true, "flavorRef": "42", "name":
"multiple-create-test-971632462", "min_count": 1, "networks": [{"uuid":
"cf357903-a60c-4b1c-8524-a0aaa4bb2fe7"}], "max_count": 2}}

When deleting an instance before it's completely built, we try to
deallocate the network and that failed since deallocate_for_instance
wasn't filtering out None addresses from requested_networks.

This fixes the problem by simply filtering the list of fixed IPs from
requested_networks before trying to deallocate the fixed IPs.

Closes-Bug: #1439302

Change-Id: I459a98151406a0b125a65b00fa0186eb5df97b1c

commit_message:
Add explicit reactive enforcment

This patch causes policy statements that use
the modal 'execute' in the heads of rules to
invoke actions implemented by datasource drivers.

Change-Id: I811a6525762284728e8276203072ae75504dcdb9

commit_message:
Fix live migration can not rollback resource correctly

When some exception occur in funciton _live_migration,
the _rollback_live_migration() will be called, and the variable
"migrate_date" must be imported, which as the specific params,
otherwise the instance path will be not deleted and causes next
live-migration to fail.

Change-Id: I1469ea7fafc9bc511f960dbec8647f734ffd6826
Closes-Bug: #1415001

commit_message:
Use the ksc Adapter instead of custom HTTPClient

Keystoneclient provides the adapter to make it easier for projects to
work with sessions. It allows more flexibility in querying the service
catalog, and additional http options in a consistent way across
projects.

Change-Id: Ief96aec1057847ac0fde14f4a98b3d7b146415a4

commit_message:
Fixes _cleanup_rbd code to capture ImageBusy exception

This patch captures the rbd.ImageBusy exception and attempts to
remove the image from the rbd volume.

Co-Authored-By: Dan Smith <dansmith@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I6a5ca4c68a39c2abf5f3f7d2d863fa2198d3c8e9
Closes-Bug: 1438331

commit_message:
Remove old relation in Cells for ComputeNode and Service

add_cell_to_service was still checking if compute_node was returned but now that
the DB model is no longer having a FK nor a relationship, it's always returning
nothing so we can fix the fake mocks and we can remove the conditional.

Change-Id: Ib8e85b3daf2c13e8b55ca33e31605abee57a03a4
Related-Bug: #1423237

fix ironic settings file to not error when sourced

is_ironic_enabled does not actually exist in the realm of things we've
sourced, so put this back to the more simple service check.

commit_message:
Add Bandit security static analysis checking via tox

The plan is to add Bandit to the commit gate.  Bandit is
produced by the OpenStack security team to do static code
analysis for security implementation failures.  It tests
the code base for ~30 common security problems in Python
with more to come.  The bandit.yaml configuration file
is set to the value recommended by the Bandit team.

run with:
    tox -e bandit

Change-Id: I46cde803119d0162b6256346e423079cadac17cb
Partially-Implements: blueprint gate-bandit

commit_message:
Fix for the launchpad bug 1440649

The patch set fixes the problem described
in the launchpad bug 1440649 where deletion
of an existing l2gw connection fails.
The code logic in the service plugin (inside
the method delete_port_mac) handled
the case where the incoming argument was a dict.
It, however, did not handle the case where
the incoming argument was a list.

Closes-Bug: 1440649
Change-Id: Id315416b12b6af581aa768c1378fae6496c342f5

commit_message:
ucast_macs and physical_locators deletion problem

The patch set fixes the problem described in
the launchpad bug 1440691 where the plugin
was not able to delete entries from
ucast_macs_remotes and physical_locators
tables when l2-gateway-connection-delete deletes
the entries from the corresponding OVSDB
server tables, and the OVSDB server sends
delete notifications to the plugin via
the L2gw agent.

Closes-Bug: 1440691
Change-Id: Ib5e18f7a278f2e8d13d5fc271826599c49b141e7

commit_message:
l2-gateway-connection-create reports OVSDBError

The patch set fixes
1. a problem described in the
bug 1440301 where the L2gateway agent throws
a syntax error as the logical switch is passed
as a list inside a list.
2. a problem where the database model
cannot store the value of the string
"unspecified-fault" in 16 character column width
for the port fault status and switch fault status.
3. a problem where the L2gateway agent and the plugin
do not handle empty port and switch fault status
which makes validation of the logical gateway fail
when an l2-gateway-connection is created.

Closes-Bug:1440301
Change-Id: Id4530b26407f2a6d57de7254476d77a36bb70a27

commit_message:
Ensure listener args are always a tuple/immutable

Make sure the arguments are not mutable and can not
be modified by anyone so that the listener maintains
a read-only state after it has been created (immutability
is typically always good & preferred).

Change-Id: I819ea43e6e7e77179e15df3ecbb7c39e96c0592f

commit_message:
websocketproxy: Make protocol validation use connection_info

With this change, we avoid the need to have config '*_baseurl' config
options correctly set up on nodes running console-proxy services, as the
access_url is now available after token validation.

UpgradeImpact: Websocket proxies need to be upgraded in a lockstep
with the API nodes up to this commit (or when upgrading to Kilo),
as older API nodes will not be sending the access_url when authorizing
console access, and newer proxy services (this commit and onward) would
fail to authorize such requests.

Change-Id: I721bca407bf9d3fb33a3461c04d392284448d4a6
Closes-bug: #1442048

commit_message:
Silently drop access to non-existent flavours

Although not ideal, users are merely confused, when an error
message pops up, but everything works.

Change-Id: I765a8ba361e47e5a0af91328865db2515e51606a

commit_message:
consoleauth: Store access_url on token authorization

Related-bug: 1409142

As part of the fix for the related bug - we've added protocol checking
to mitigate MITM attacks, however we base protocol checking on a config
option that is normally only intended for compute hosts.

This is quite user hostile, as it is now important that all nodes
running compute and proxy services have this option in sync.

We can do better than that - we can persist the URL the client is
expected to use, and once we get it back on token validation, we can
make sure that the request is using the intended protocol, mitigating
the MITM injected script attacks.

This patch makes sure that the access_url is persisted with the token -
the follow-up patch makes consoles use that info.

Change-Id: I02a377f54de46536ca35413b615d3298967afc33

commit_message:
consoleauth: remove an instance of mutation while iterating

Mutating a list while iterating over it is a big python no-no. Let's not
do it in consoleauth service anymore.

Change-Id: I50d201f3f39576d7a32b722ead0667fd9abaeb75

commit_message:
requests skip 2.2.1

keystoneclient unit tests are failing with requests 2.2.1. The next
release is 2.3.0, and that works, so use that.

The failure is like:

  Traceback (most recent call last):
   File "keystoneclient/tests/v3/test_auth_saml2.py", line 621, in test_end_to_end_workflow
     token, token_json = self.adfsplugin._get_unscoped_token(self.session)
 ...
  File "/opt/stack/python-keystoneclient/.tox/py27/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/requests/cookies.py", line 128, in extract_cookies_to_jar
    jar.extract_cookies(res, req)
 AttributeError: 'list' object has no attribute 'extract_cookies'

Change-Id: I45339208e473bdd3afe09b1623b7321927614c8b

commit_message:
Add json-schema for v2.1 fixed-ips

This patch adds json-schema for v2.1 fixed-ips. The json-schame limits
the input for actions reserve/unreserve. Also fixed the API sample
file at same time and add parameter_type none.

Co-Authored-By: Ken'ichi Ohmichi <ken1ohmichi@gmail.com>
Change-Id: Id2d0416c3ccc2a50d3cb66bed8747082f98fb194
Closes-Bug: #1438480

commit_message:
GlusterFS: Returning provider location of volume from snapshot

This patch returns the provider location of volume, which is
created from snapshot.

Partial-Bug: 1441050
Reported-By: Deepak C Shetty <deepakcs@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I5994f2f6c125888d442055d9e65355f0af1b22f4

commit_message:
Disable redundant functionality with env creation

In case there are no environments,
there are two options for creating a new one.
It's confusing and main table button is hidden until first environment creation.

Change-Id: I7ca2d39eb69ecaa2d0ec1bfbe352fce0ff4041f3
Closes-Bug: #1442667

[{'created': '2015-04-10 15:31:48.000000000', 'message': "Forbid the user to specify custom ports during creating docker-apps

At the moment there is no mechanism to change container port for
application. Thus, we shouldn't allow the user to specify custom
ports apart from cases when application requires explicit network
configuration and ports must be specified as environment variables

Change-Id: I66a2db8ab7709e7d3ecc88547d97111f4179f267
Closes-Bug: #1442154
"}]
commit_message:
Forbid the user to specify custom ports during creating docker-apps

At the moment there is no mechanism to change container port for
application. Thus, we shouldn't allow the user to specify custom
ports apart from cases when application requires explicit network
configuration and ports must be specified as environment variables

Change-Id: I66a2db8ab7709e7d3ecc88547d97111f4179f267
Closes-Bug: #1442154

commit_message:
Fix style of app tiles

* Now all tiles have same size.
* App name replaces with ellipsis is it's too long.
* App name is shown on mouse enter in case of overflow.


Change-Id: Ic9a86211a2af13e72027895764071457cc21cb56
Closes-Bug: #1439294

commit_message:
Tag all Swift packages

Some users wish to override the default package provider by their own.

Tag all packages with the 'openstack' to allow mass resource attributes
override using resource collectors.

Change-Id: Ib0cec660f134e266006f41572cafcc4661ca1e67
Closes-bug: #1391209
Signed-off-by: Gael Chamoulaud <gchamoul@redhat.com>

In the delete_snapshot API, the Gluster command issued to delete the
snapshot ends up being run in the interactive mode of the
Gluster-CLI. So instead of an XML output, the command results in a
Gluster-CLI read error. Fix this by forcing the Gluster command to be

commit_message:
glusterfs_native: Fix Gluster command call

In the delete_snapshot API, the Gluster command issued to delete the
snapshot ends up being run in the interactive mode of the
Gluster-CLI. So instead of an XML output, the command results in a
Gluster-CLI read error. Fix this by forcing the Gluster command to be
run in the script mode.

Change-Id: Ic09f59732bf08942a9d216f70f1fc969d9ae0a2d
Closes-Bug: #1442339

commit_message:
Update Fuel-Devops documentation

* Fuel-Devops is now separated to
Version 2.5.x and 2.9.x.
* Installation can be implemented
via PyPI in Python virtual env.

Change-Id: I6083964a51b219c2dcffd517d4d80b7f3288f22f
Closes-bug: #1430314

commit_message:
glusterfs, glusterfs_native: perform version checks

- add gluster_version method to GlusterManager class
- gluster: check if version of the GlusterFS server is at least 3.5
- gluster_native: check if version of the GlusterFS server is at least 3.6
- gluster_native: on snaphot creation failure, interpret errno only
  for GlusterFS strictly later than 3.6

Change-Id: I242ea83c3a31670eb6a13c11e39d0c2228170c50
Closes-Bug: #1417352

commit_message:
Add object caching in manila REST API requests

Allow the core API to cache resources, such as DB results, so that
extensions can use data already retrieved within the same API request
eliminating additional expensive DB calls.

Loosely based on Cinder commits 233430b51ddbd207f22eee98386ffbb766fd777f
and 4aeb7256ef4cc75bae4ff9258a5bcf6092b3c834. Which are based on Nova
commit 9f9fbc54e7336da10fc3056bdaca2ec7d01c7f94

Use caching for share types to avoid concurrency issue when listing of
share types request was getting response from another request.

Change-Id: I8bb3d9af0ee36d0c7b80f979ef1ce6eafb2f6ced
Closes-Bug: #1441602

commit_message:
VMware: Fix missing target resource pool

The volume is cloned while creating it from another volume, snapshot
or image. Currently, the target resource pool is unset while calling
vCenter CloneVM_Task API.

So when a clone happens across clusters in a vCenter clone fails.
This patch fixes the problem by setting the target resource pool
(returned by datastore selection logic) while invoking clone.

Closes-Bug: #1416456

Change-Id: Ib1023efe6fd19d604af89f7e4b4f67640d778d39

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-10 20:15:46.000000000', 'message': 'Mock out base share driver __init__ in EMC driver

Two EMC driver unit tests failed because it failed to load Neutron
network plugins. This is because stevedore.extension.ExtensionManager
is mocked to return [] for the EMC parent driver (EMC parent driver
uses stevedore framework to load backend plugins such as VNX and
Isilon), however, the base share driver tries to load Neutron network
plugins and expects the list to be non-empty.

This patch mocks out the base share driver __init__ method so that
it will not try to initialize the base class and will not try to
load the Neutron network plugin.

Change-Id: I57ff71f638b48c1485b32401addc909002fdc768
Closes-Bug: #1442788
'}]
commit_message:
Mock out base share driver __init__ in EMC driver

Two EMC driver unit tests failed because it failed to load Neutron
network plugins. This is because stevedore.extension.ExtensionManager
is mocked to return [] for the EMC parent driver (EMC parent driver
uses stevedore framework to load backend plugins such as VNX and
Isilon), however, the base share driver tries to load Neutron network
plugins and expects the list to be non-empty.

This patch mocks out the base share driver __init__ method so that
it will not try to initialize the base class and will not try to
load the Neutron network plugin.

Change-Id: I57ff71f638b48c1485b32401addc909002fdc768
Closes-Bug: #1442788

commit_message:
Add service_bindings table to cloudfoundryv2 driver

This also bumps the requirement of the python-cloudfoundryclient to 1.0.2 as
this new method only became present in the 1.0.2 release of
python-cloudfoundryclient.

commit_message:
Add murano environments to murano datasource tables and fix bugs

Includes environment in the parent_types and relationships
datasource tables. Also fixes a bug where parent_types entries of
an application/service are missing if its type prefix is not
'io.murano.apps' as in the case of MySql ('io.murano.databases.mysql')
Now service type is checked against loaded application packages so
that the service type is properly identified. If its type is not
found then its type prefix is used for identifying its type as the
last resort.

Implements: blueprint murano-driver

Change-Id: I9b5fcbade1398678238ac6b470d4eccdd1ffc893

commit_message:
Track modals in dependency graph of agnostic policy engine

This change adds a datastructure that keeps track of the tables
that exist for each modal in the head of rules.

The motivating use case is setting up triggers for implementing
explicit reactive enforcment.

Change-Id: I4f7bf09f2d8158a2ee4301d0eb12d6792b2aac03

commit_message:
Add modal field to agnostic policy engine trigger registry

Previously, registering a trigger allowed you to choose the
policy and the tablename, but not the modal.

This change allows you to also choose the modal.

Change-Id: I53c9bc58632ef803f5624dfc69ae0c1ade4a5f71

commit_message:
Refactor MemcachedBackend to not be a Manager

The MemcachedBackend class doesn't act like a normal Manager since
it doesn't use the superclass to import the driver. All it did is
forward item references to the driver, but this is obvious and easy
enough to implement locally. Making MemcachedBackend not subclass
from Manager makes subclasses of Manager consistent.

bp stevedore

Change-Id: I1d865220e8225bf7a9a1b016eea1d364c70ed832

If the neutron server is down, 120 seconds is far too long to wait for
puppet to fail. This patch reduces the timeout to 10 seconds because if

Change-Id: I7bd694d1e5ee3477f7ea862965f7f3368903abde

commit_message:
Reduce neutron API timeout to 10 seconds

If the neutron server is down, 120 seconds is far too long to wait for
puppet to fail. This patch reduces the timeout to 10 seconds because if
the neutron server is flaky, but not down, 10 seconds is a reasonable
amount of time to retry connecting.

Change-Id: I7bd694d1e5ee3477f7ea862965f7f3368903abde

commit_message:
Move rbd related options into glance_store section

From Juno release, rbd related options has been move into
glance_store section.
See more info:
http://docs.openstack.org/juno/config-reference/content/section_glance-api.conf.html

Closes-Bug: #1436699
(cherry picked from commit 101ca5b088f3aec5d70c567f29dfdfa5609524ab)

Conflicts:
	spec/classes/glance_backend_rbd_spec.rb

Change-Id: I449b0e4d2205f0b81d6bb8c97e44a03b3b107453

commit_message:
[Launch Instance Fix] Show volume device name

When setting a volume, allow setting the volume device name if supported

Note: To test, you need to add the following to local_settings.py

REST_API_REQUIRED_SETTINGS = ['OPENSTACK_HYPERVISOR_FEATURES']

OPENSTACK_HYPERVISOR_FEATURES = {
    'can_set_mount_point': True
}

Change can_set_mount_point to False to see it not show up.
Must restart the server.

Co-Authored-By: Brian Tully <brian.tully@hp.com>
Change-Id: Ied8b1e92ea361fa5806128a71d6815e4b1494272
Closes-Bug: #1439906

This variable is better renamed to 'topics' to
match the typical message queue kind of syntax/usage since
each entry in this dictionary is nearly equivalent to a
specific topic channel about a event (with the dictionary
value being the set of targets/listeners that are registered

commit_message:
Rename notifier 'listeners' to 'topics'

This variable is better renamed to 'topics' to
match the typical message queue kind of syntax/usage since
each entry in this dictionary is nearly equivalent to a
specific topic channel about a event (with the dictionary
value being the set of targets/listeners that are registered
on that channel who will get notified about any channel/topic
activity).

Change-Id: Ie76e9cc4e29f4e542be987561cd6872e021cfa58

commit_message:
Fix order listing on the command line.

This makes the 2 different orders have the same fields displayed, so
that we can list them in the same table.

Change-Id: I432911ea32af7642d6d56f0dc07bdd502f2b1a94
Closes-Bug: #1438901

commit_message:
Updates Heat template Compose and Kolla Repositories

Previously, compose was being pulled from sdake. Since pull 1011
for pid=host support was merged, we can now use the upstream repo.

Additionally, the heat template was using the Kolla ml-3 release.
Since ml3 was cut, trunk should be reverted to using Kolla trunk.

Change-Id: I44ad01ee9fde914c87d981c05b825fa549420f8c

commit_message:
[Launch Instance Fix] Settings for volume name

This patch provides the rest API needed to
get settings that allow conditionally
displaying the volume device name
and admin password.

Examples:

settingsService.ifEnabled('setting').then(doThis);
settingsService.ifEnabled('setting', 'expected', 'default').then(doThis, elseThis);

Change-Id: I8d16f4b974786157c5aa562e2675e6e60aabc412
Partial-Bug: #1439906
Partial-Bug: #1439905

commit_message:
Add Functional Tests for Private Key Secret Type

Add two functional tests that generate secrets from
two different libraries (OpenSSL and PyCrypto).  Prove
that each generated private key can be stored, retreived,
consumed, and have the result match the original.

Change-Id: Ifac00999cf36945d79371ffb8152fdf31efe9585

commit_message:
modularize mysql db saving

let projects declare that they will have a database to be saved, and
we'll do it for them, in the mysql case. Eventually other saving
issues should be left to per project save-state.sh scripts.

services which aren't always enabled in grenade jobs have their
settings files guarded with conditionals. Eventually we'll do
conditional loading of these settings files, however for now this lets
the rest of the infrastructure around running actions based on
PLUGIN_DIRS and UPGRADE_SERVICES be *non* conditional, which
simplifies them.

Change-Id: I06cad95ca319e4403772e5fb394c0f8965e0bf9d

commit_message:
always install the exit trap in scripts

This moves the exit trap into grenade/functions, which means all
grenade scripts will get the exit trap registered on them. This also
adds stack tracing into the scripts so that we can determine where we
were when we failed.

Change-Id: I4100628180498ff8723a1af6c0a4c10b4d8244c8

commit_message:
reorder imports in stand alone scripts

$GRENADE_DIR/functions pulls in devstack functions, and needs
$GRENADE_DIR/grenaderc to be sourced first. Do this for all affected
scripts.

stop-base also needs the grenade.settings file as that handles all the
partial services.

reorder clean.sh to remove warnings

Change-Id: I5baa17783abe0c235691d88e484331c7960549f9

commit_message:
Shorten HTTP request timeout length

If a service is really not available and not just in the middle of
refreshing, it will be apparent relatively quickly. There is no need to
have the user wait 120 seconds to fail. This patch decreases the
timeout length to 10 seconds.

Change-Id: Ia9e13bd6c6f867b00f0a14ccff86cb3ab52f9fe3
(cherry picked from commit eb4f43e25cc40160980bf1fc45a48e1abe147d65)

commit_message:
Merge baremetal_nodes func tests between V2 and V2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges baremetal_nodes functional tests.

Change-Id: Ifb42121727ae8ad1eebbdff3e52f2af816ccae28

commit_message:
Rename TOSCA AttachTo relationship

The AttachTo relationship name has been changed to AttachesTo per the latest
TOSCA spec to be consistent with naming like BindsTo, ConnectsTo etc.

Change-Id: Ibd0e0232a06b02c494def452755422ab94c4024e

commit_message:
Shorten HTTP request timeout length

If a service is really not available and not just in the middle of
refreshing, it will be apparent relatively quickly. There is no need to
have the user wait 120 seconds to fail. This patch decreases the
timeout length to 10 seconds.

Change-Id: Ia9e13bd6c6f867b00f0a14ccff86cb3ab52f9fe3

commit_message:
Change check_child_processes_interval default

Change this default value from 0 to 30 will enable agents moniter
external processes and respawn them when them get killed

Closes-Bug: #1437108
Change-Id: I9ccfd405e883be895304bac85cc86d4984ac42c8

commit_message:
Fix broken unit tests for networking-odl

Commit 1105782e3914f601b8f4be64939816b1afe8fb54 on the Neutron side
reorganized unit tests. This fixes the location of test_ml2_plugin,
which is imported by the networking-odl unit tests code, and
consequently revives successful unit test runs for networking-odl.

Change-Id: I1b517b907c4bf88bdf89dc2532b6b3a24ff57309

commit_message:
Use a sentinel connection pool to manage failover

When configured to use sentinel with the redis driver, allow the
redis-py client to manage the connection to the currently elected
master.

'master_for' will return a StricRedis client which is bound to a
connection pool that queries the Sentinel[s] when providing
connections from the pool.

This means that failover handling is automatic as long as the
sentinels can be reached and they have elected a new master.

Change-Id: I8fd672e664d98097944a7c984cadab5fb08dd2d6
Closes-Bug: #1434043
(cherry picked from commit 54d6bb1c94270d2794ecefbcaf3f8832010e3d58)

commit_message:
fix mysql driver url parsing

Used 'parsed_url.hostname' instead of 'parsed_url.netloc' to get hostname.

Changed setup-mysql-env.sh script to start 'mysqld' with networking.

Closes-Bug: 1426351
Change-Id: Ifcf68b10ef5f93864d33d3a1719b9be321db6e5c
(cherry picked from commit 6ea2302ccf702ffc447020139111e5f9a2629314)

commit_message:
Updating the disk image builder code

Adds haproxy 1.5.x from ubuntu trusty backports
Adds a git pull for the amphora agent code
Removes check for argparse (internal for python 2.7)
Adds sysctl net.ipv4.ip_nonlocal_bind=1

Change-Id: I7aecf727fb5d9be08982c5a32ae3c6e280ebda14

subject: Fix caching bug in create_volume/list_volume
messages:
[{'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2015-04-07 01:18:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2015-04-07 01:25:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3099, 'date': '2015-04-07 01:35:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Why does this problem occur if the null backend is used? My understanding is that the null backend does NO caching:

https://dogpilecache.readthedocs.org/en/latest/api.html#null-backend

So even if we ignore the value of the 'cache' parameter (which we *totally* should not do), it should still go through _get_volumes_from_cloud() to get the object, shouldn't it?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-07 01:44:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-shade-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/15/171015/2/check/gate-shade-pep8/4c4507a/ : SUCCESS in 2m 23s
- gate-shade-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/15/171015/2/check/gate-shade-docs/0f887c8//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 26s
- gate-shade-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/15/171015/2/check/gate-shade-python27/10efb13/ : SUCCESS in 2m 59s
- gate-shade-python34 http://logs.openstack.org/15/171015/2/check/gate-shade-python34/3125fdb/ : SUCCESS in 3m 56s
- check-shade-dsvm-functional http://logs.openstack.org/15/171015/2/check/check-shade-dsvm-functional/38d664e/ : SUCCESS in 18m 35s'}, {'account_id': 3099, 'date': '2015-04-07 12:58:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

+1 because this change is needed. The null driver not working as expected is a separate issue.'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2015-04-07 13:36:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I don't think this really fixes it, because subsequent calls that aren't specifically part of the attach flow will continue to get old data. SO - skipping the cache is fine in the flow - but we're also going to need a cache invalidation once the operation is successful ... or at some point."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2015-04-08 17:04:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I do agree that invalidation on creation is important. Working on it in I0f10d8f7f1c6847d6122b7631306db292eaa8b8f . Though realistically, the volume list may just be a bad choice for caching altogether. It is a vibrant set of data that we almost never want to look at except to see if changes have ocurred (unlike projects, flavors, etc. which almost never change). What we might also want to do is reduce expire time to very low for the volume list. Ultimately though, for things that change a lot, what we really want is an event stream, which OpenStack just doesn't give us."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2015-04-10 21:37:27.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

There are several things wrong here and a different approach is needed. I'm thinking more and more that instead of cache=False, we should push hard to invalidate whenever the user or even shade suspects any state should be changing. For instance, if 'creating' is the state, we don't ever want to cache that list, since we know it will be either error, or active, at some point."}]

commit_message:
Fix caching bug in create_volume/list_volume

We need to respect the 'cache' flag passed in to list_volumes, but we
were ignoring it.

This causes problems if a volume moves from 'creating' to 'available',
so adding a test to make sure that works.

Change-Id: I5d2c36b4402cd099f3d7810feccd76693b786f76

commit_message:
Apply a naming rule of GET to orchestration client

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s"
or "show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the rule
to orchestration client.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I5a0d046d3811d48d3e4bddae8b0f022762c621c8

subject: Apply a naming rule of GET to volume client

commit_message:
Apply a naming rule of GET to volume client

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s"
or "show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the rule
to volume client.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I843dd43293f40bf673a033b1dbf24e035bc8f0c3

commit_message:
Change domain_id FK in project table

This patch partially implements Reseller.
Previous patches did:

- Honor domain operations in project table
- Stop calling domain drivers

This patch update the Fk to domain_id in the Project Table
that before pointed to the Domain Table and now will point
to the Project table.

Change-Id: I8ab47ec961362c8420a97617c4fb17a349fcc6a3
Implements: bp reseller

[{'created': '2015-03-20 22:21:18.000000000', 'message': 'WIP: Release bdm constraint source and dest type

https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1377958 fixed a problem
that source_type: image, destination_type: local is not
supported for boot instance, exception should be raised to
reject the param otherwise it will lead to instance become
ERROR state.

However the fix introduced a problem on nova client
https://bugs.launchpad.net/python-novaclient/+bug/1418484
The fix of the bug leads to following command become invalid

nova boot test-vm --flavor m1.medium --image centos-vm-32
--nic net-id=c3f40e33-d535-4217-916b-1450b8cd3987 --block-device
id=26b7b917-2794-452a-95e5-2efb2ca6e32d,bus=sata,source=volume,bootindex=1

So we need to release the original constraint to allow
the above special case pass the validation check then
we can revert the nova client exception (another patch)

This patch checks the boot_index and whether image param is
given after we found the bdm has source_type: image,
destination_type: local, if this is the special case, then
no exception will be raised.

Closes-Bug: #1433609

Change-Id: If43faae95169bc3864449a8364975f5c887aac14

commit_message:
Release bdm constraint source and dest type

https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1377958 fixed a problem
that source_type: image, destination_type: local is not
supported for boot instance, exception should be raised to
reject the param otherwise it will lead to instance become
ERROR state.

However the fix introduced a problem on nova client
https://bugs.launchpad.net/python-novaclient/+bug/1418484
The fix of the bug leads to following command become invalid

nova boot test-vm --flavor m1.medium --image centos-vm-32
--nic net-id=c3f40e33-d535-4217-916b-1450b8cd3987 --block-device
id=26b7b917-2794-452a-95e5-2efb2ca6e32d,bus=sata,source=volume,bootindex=1

So we need to release the original constraint to allow
the above special case pass the validation check then
we can revert the nova client exception
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/165932/)

This patch checks the boot_index and whether image param is
given after we found the bdm has source_type: image,
destination_type: local, if this is the special case, then
no exception will be raised.

Closes-Bug: #1433609

Andreas has the correct understanding, keyring is not supported in OSC. KSC still supports it.

It would be nice to explain to the user why setting your password as an env. var or in the command line is a bad idea, and encourage them to *not* set it. OSC will prompt for a password instead.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-04-09 04:50:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Removes a Keyring support section from End User Guide

As keyring encryption support was removed from openstackclient code,
the End User Guide was updated as well by removing Keyring support
section from appropriate chapter in the user guide.

Change-Id: I9531b460be9a4dd2d6c1aedb33324fd9140a4538
Closes-Bug: #1419990

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
add INFO level logging for the django dashboard

This will make the django dashboard log in /mnt/state/var/log/horizon
as it happens already for other components.

The django logging dict is appended into local_settings.py only if
no lines defining the logging are found to be there already.

The logging settings are taken from the defaults found in the
local_settings.py.example file shipped with horizon.

Change-Id: Idd957ae4ff5f71a5949dc8703bd29398b32c4498

commit_message:
Added Raw Value Loading to Test Fixture

This patch adds a method by which raw key/value pairs may be
loaded into the test fixture, without them being registered
first. Tests have been provided.

commit_message:
Fixed order of arguments during execution live_migrate()

order of arguments that passed to
ComputeManager.live_,migration() differs in ComputeManager and
_ComputeV4Proxy classes

hi james, thanks for reviewing'}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2014-12-05 07:59:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

my only reservation is that this was done [1] (ish)  & reverted [2] a while ago. I *think* the revert was more about the temp check for the heat template change rather than the introduction of new vars. From a quick look seems the heat templates are all setup to accept these. I'd be interested to hear more from jp (will ping him) about the revert, thanks

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/108412/4
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/109100/1"}, {'account_id': 215, 'date': '2014-12-05 12:04:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The reason to reject this previously is because it is unnecessary - all of the data can be put into the heat environment file.'}, {'account_id': 13945, 'date': '2014-12-09 03:11:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2014-12-16 20:37:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I'm going to -1 based on JP's comment, but I'm open to discussion if there's a reason the env file can't be used for this."}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2015-01-13 07:17:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Giulio what do you think ?'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2015-01-13 08:43:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

hi Marios, thanks for pinging. I think we should give users a pattern so that they know if their first spot should be the env vars or the env file. And if we need both, try to be clear about what is expected to be changed via the env vars and what in the env file.

I also understand we don't want to add more end but this is a peculiar case given the shared ExtraConfig param is already taken from env so it would make sense, at least for me, to add support for the role specific ExtraConfig.

Finally, this could be just my laziness but do we have any section in the doc explaining how to hack into the env file at all?"}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2015-01-23 07:29:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

(1 comment)

I'm on the fence about this.

I don't like adding 3 new extra env vars, and I don't like having to pass them through so many times in so many places.

I think I'd prefer to see a single "overcloud-env.yaml" file which has sections for nova, compute etc - and then we just need to pass in one file with one variable. 

On the other hand, that one file is likely to become quite large and unwieldy.

I'd like to go with the solution that's easier for deployers, but I'm not sure which solution that would be.

My understanding is that before this change we have no way to pass in the nova, compute etc extra configs.

On balance, I'm going go give this a +2. I'm not convinced it's the best possible answer; but it's the best answer we have right now, and I'd rather us try this out and refine it later than to make it easier for deployers to use. However, if I'm wrong, and there is already some other way to pass in all the extra configs, then I think I'd like to see more discussoin (maybe a spec?) about which alternative is going to be easier for deployers before we go ahead with this.'}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2015-01-27 07:58:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

(1 comment)

did a little digging - compute+control extra config were introduced in [1] and the block storage in [2] (for heat templates). As tchaypo says I can only see the general OVERCLOUD_EXTRA_CONFIG being set in incubator scripts.

I think it would be nice to have a discussion and (possibly assuming volunteer and time) a writeup about how we can pass params consistently but I don't think we should block on this change for that. The particular params in questino here were introduced ages ago and just aren't being consumed.


[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/108415/

[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/112075/"}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2015-01-27 23:02:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

So I'd still rather not do this.  Input env vars need to DIAF.

That said, I don't know for sure how it would work to embed json in json.  Will heat do the right thing if we just did "NovaComputeExtraConfig": {...extra config json...} or do we have to encode the extra config json into a string that could be embedded in the json file?  If the latter then I guess I would find it more difficult to argue against the env vars (except that doing the "good enough" thing is why our ui is such a disaster...).

My main takeaway is that we _really_ need the rationalize-ui spec. :-/'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2015-01-28 10:54:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

my idea is that we should take a decision, because we do not hate users indeed; so I suggest we either allow passing ExtraConfig via an ENV var for all the node types (and merge this change) or we suggest to pass ExtraConfig in the json file (and drop support for generic OVERCLOUD_EXTRA_CONFIG as well)'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2015-04-09 21:09:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I'd rather see us provide a more pluggable mechanism (perhaps using Heat environments) to allow users to customize settings like this.

Continually adding ENV variables to the devtest_overcloud.sh script isn't scalable."}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2015-04-10 20:01:09.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Consume OVERCLOUD_*_EXTRA_CONFIG from env for Passthrough

This ensures final template is provided with the specific node
type ExtraConfig data (eg. controllerExtraConfig)

Change-Id: I49ffd50cbb6c3fe196a679965a2b669f0f7091c9

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-10 14:06:03.000000000', 'message': 'Fix check_can_live_migrate_destination() in ComputeV4Proxy

There was a mismatch in the V4 proxy in the call signatures of this
function. This was missed because the "destination" parameter is passed
in the rpcapi as the host to contact, which is consumed by the rpc
layer and not passed. Since it was not called one of the standard
names (either host if to be not passed, or host_param if to be passed),
this was missed.

Change-Id: Idf2160934dade650ed02b672f3b64cb26247f8e6
Closes-Bug: #1442602
'}]
commit_message:
Fix check_can_live_migrate_destination() in ComputeV4Proxy

There was a mismatch in the V4 proxy in the call signatures of this
function. This was missed because the "destination" parameter is passed
in the rpcapi as the host to contact, which is consumed by the rpc
layer and not passed. Since it was not called one of the standard
names (either host if to be not passed, or host_param if to be passed),
this was missed.

Change-Id: Idf2160934dade650ed02b672f3b64cb26247f8e6
Closes-Bug: #1442602

On some environments, especially on small instances
with slow internet connection deployment may fail.

In this change:
- Added retry procedure.
- Adjusted timeouts.
- Improved logging.

Change-Id: Ic0dbe73b5d7a90c1de86ffa0029a0fefd029b15b

commit_message:
CloudFoundry deployment fixes

On some environments, especially on small instances
with slow internet connection deployment may fail.

In this change:
- Added retry procedure.
- Adjusted timeouts.
- Improved logging.

Change-Id: Ic0dbe73b5d7a90c1de86ffa0029a0fefd029b15b

commit_message:
Refactored github tools to prefer token-based auth

The github workflow still asks for username, password,
and 2FA token if need be, but creates a repo token and
uses that for further exchanges to save on user input
fatigue.

Closes-Bug: #1442764

Change-Id: I530a965dc5d5bad080c49b5cf0d38f3f7aee201a

commit_message:
Adds 'solum info' and 'solum --version' to help

Those two help methods have been available for
some time; excluding them from help messages
was an oversight.

Closes-Bug: #1442757

Change-Id: Ib82c6c51991d835674ad0b1a7d17d6963205e2ca

commit_message:
Share V2 and V2.1 tenant-networks functional tests

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges tenant-networks functional tests.

Change-Id: I470ce6d26cd0865d2645ef269aa419b2b200ac37

commit_message:
Default app status to REGISTERED

If an app is new or simply owns no assemblies, display a status
of REGISTERED instead of an empty list. This also helps convey
that creating (registering) an app does not immediately invoke
the test/build/deploy process.

Closes-Bug: #1430522

Change-Id: I24aa0170a0228ed6e097203edb3cb76101745260

commit_message:
Doc updates for Certificates for PKI

There were several issuses with the "Certificates for PKI"
subsection of the "Identity management" section of the Cloud
Administrator Guide.

- Keystone doesn't have a token_format or ca_password setting in
  the [signing] section of its config file, so the doc shouldn't
  say that there is one.

- Keystone does have a cert_subject option, so add that for
  completeness.

- The token provider class is now used instead of token_format.

commit_message:
MariaDB bind on correct address

Despite passing bind-address for MariaDB in overcloud_controller.pp
correctly, it was always trying to bind on 0.0.0.0. The problem is
caused by Galera's config file (we install Galera into the image even
though we don't use it yet). Galera's default config file contains
override of the bind-address value to 0.0.0.0, and the setting from
galera.cnf took precendence over what was in server.cnf.

The mariadb-galera-server package assumes that the main config happens
in galera.cnf and it ships an almost empty server.cnf. We now have an
EnableGalera param, when it's set to true the mysql module will manage
galera.cnf instead of server.cnf, overriding the default values from
galera.cnf and fixing the issue.

Change-Id: I7c2fd41d41dcf5eb4ee8b1dbd74d60cc2cabeed9
Closes-Bug: #1442256

commit_message:
fixing taskflow.flow tests

- Added a __init__.py to cue/tests/taskflow/flow to have it recognized
  as a module

commit_message:
Merge sec grp default rules tests between V2 and V2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges sec grp default rules functional tests.

Change-Id: I3a00d86c3c5451473601bd330015ccef4cf5c2a2

commit_message:
Removes router binding with router-interface-delete

Today when an interface is deleted from a dvr router
the binding with the l3-agent is not removed for the
qrouter.

This patch will try to remove the binding with all
the l3 agents for the specific router if there are
no other subnets attached to the router.

This will also trigger the agent to remove the
namespaces if configured to do so.

Change-Id: I29a2e3009114728b96429939804fcc7f3cb25281
Closes-Bug: #1413630

commit_message:
Fix test_as_root* tests to work when run as root

While using docker to test this module, I discovered that the
test suite does not pass because the processutils.execute() code
will not prepend the root helper because it already has root
permissions, which results in the shell trying to execute the
command 'a b c', rather than 'echo a b c'.

Change-Id: Id3429f06d6a0353f1cc4520af6daceed48c30071

The "insecure" option was being treated as a bool when it was
actually provided as a string. The fix is to parse the string to

Closes-Bug: 1411063
Change-Id: I508dae8d7bedfc903e476cdefac43d05cbd7fbe1
'}]
commit_message:
Fix s3_token middleware parsing insecure option

The "insecure" option was being treated as a bool when it was
actually provided as a string. The fix is to parse the string to
a bool.

Closes-Bug: 1411063
Change-Id: I508dae8d7bedfc903e476cdefac43d05cbd7fbe1

TOSCA: Create new utils module with memory units

Create new functions to handle memory units. These functions are created as
common utils for general use. Because of new module dependency unit tests are
created in a following patch.

Change-Id: I93af33c5a98b7f5afd66d32f167cfad0f7d3d1fe

TOSCA: Create new utils module with memory units

Create new functions to handle memory units. These functions are created as
common utils for general use. Because of new module dependency unit tests are
created in a following patch.

Change-Id: I93af33c5a98b7f5afd66d32f167cfad0f7d3d1fe

We discussed voting permissions for CI's and decided against it.

http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/cinder/2014/cinder.2014-10-15-16.00.log.html

That was October 2014 though, and I do agree the Ceph CI has been stable. This sounds like a good opportunity for us to begin steps for Cinder volume driver CI's voting! Exciting!"}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2015-04-07 07:12:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

We specifically discussed whether to make this (or gluster, or sheepdog) voting and decided unambiguously against it. Until there's another discussion of the pros & cons, I'm against it.

If we make some drivers CI (other than the reference one) voting and others not, it creates a situation where changes that break some drivers can be merged and need to be fixed up by the maintainer, but for other drivers they are blocked. This was a worry I expressed when we allowed jenkins to run some thrid party CI, and I was told that it is fine because these won't become voting."}, {'account_id': 170, 'date': '2015-04-07 14:13:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

Duncan makes a fair point here. Matt, it just so happens our meeting is tomorrow if you or someone representing this patch would like to discuss this:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/CinderMeetings#Next_meeting'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-04-07 15:54:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Duncan / Mike, note that this isn't third party CI for a vendor driver, this is a job that's managed on the community infrastructure.

We could make the job non-voting for Cinder, but that's unfair to nova and glance if it's voting for those projects and someone comes along and breaks the ceph driver in Cinder because the job was non-voting, thus blocking changes from landing for nova/glance."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-04-07 15:57:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Right, it's not a third party driver, so I think it should be included for all of us. Further, it's the only way we have currently to test all the RBD bits in these projects with fully open, fully-in-upstream-infra resources. This adds a lot of coverage for those paths *without* needing anything third party."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-04-07 16:09:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 170, 'date': '2015-04-07 16:40:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Matt and Dan, these are great points. Regardless I think it should be rediscussed in the Cinder meeting since the Cinder team has decided against allowing volume drivers to have voting permission:

http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/cinder/2014/cinder.2014-10-15-16.00.log.html

This decision is quite dated, so I don't think this is off the table, I just think it's fair to be raised in the meeting for rediscussion."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-04-07 17:16:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Yep, meat to say: "happy to come to the meeting to discuss" :)'}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2015-04-08 16:49:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

So we discussed it at the meeting and decided that anybody can sponsor any of the opensource drivers hosted by infra to become voting, pending 30 days of stability. commit_message:
Make (check|gate)-tempest-dsvm-full-ceph voting for cinder/glance/nova

The ceph job has been passing on master for awhile except for when
test_volume_boot_pattern was enabled again which has problems with a
ceph backend. There is a Tempest change to skip that test when using
ceph until the bug is fixed, but we'd like to get the ceph job voting so
we don't regress it further with new changes.

This also makes the job voting on glance changes since it's configured
to use the rbd store in glance so we don't want glance changes
regressing it either.

Depends-On: Ia1cba598a8243dd4a48613c870a25de578b79fe4

Change-Id: Ia68cb013818f26bed093dbf8a989e74d7c6f8cac

commit_message:
Make the ceph jobs fetch an image-based cirros and use it by default

Cinder (ceph driver) bug 1439371 means that UEC images don't work for
boot-from-volume with ceph. This works around that problem by using an
actual image (which we probably should be doing more of, given that it
is likely a more common scenario for many deployments).

Change-Id: I201b89a3da92d8df18d0db30b9664ba4fadd5a9c

commit_message:
Get whole resource type instead of resource type ID

Update metadefs broke db export_metadefs command. It raises
NoSuchColumnError. This is because _get_resource_type method
returns only resource type ID instead of whole resource type.
To fix this issue _get_resource_type should return all resource
type columns from DB.

Change-Id: I375aaae7b4439027501f4f09d413cb607d2461b7
Closes-Bug: #1439221

commit_message:
Change proposals fall back on proposed branches

During the RC period for a project, there may already be a stable
branch for the release on the triggering project and a proposed
branch on the target project. If so, we want stable changes proposed
to the proposed branch. That's not confusing!

Change-Id: I488bb9ff63daf9d012e41dbaa178b1656eaeffad

commit_message:
Temporarily remove dashboard

The dashboard package is currently not installable because its
dependency info isn't current (doesn't work with Kilo packages). We need
to remove it from controller image to unblock TripleO CI. It can be
re-added when we have a working dashboard package.

Change-Id: Iccc708664b1c018d8712d99de755ef43351635a6

commit_message:
Merge instance_usage_audit_log tests between V2 and V2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges instance_usage_audit_log functional tests.

Change-Id: I08bca29e48fdf00f02d77f5332a93c2db14a3551

for the juno -> kilo upgrade, specifically around how to upgrade

commit_message:
Fix for automated boot iso issue with IPA ramdisk

Autogenerated boot iso for iscsi_ilo driver fails when
Fedora based IPA ramdisk is used for deploy in UEFI boot mode.
The keywords used (linux and initrd) in grub.cfg template are
specific to Ubuntu only. They are not recognized by Fedora.
Have changed it to keywords (linuxefi and initrdefi) which are
recognized by both Ubuntu and Fedora deploy ramdisks.

Also the menuentry name has been changed to 'boot_partition' in
grub config file. This is done to make it consistent with pxe
driver's elilo config file wherein menuentry name for the final
boot of user image is 'boot_partition'.

Closes-Bug: 1441691

Change-Id: Ia6fdbf4868e6606a18b33ce2b75f29f701a31b35

commit_message:
Merging instance_actions tests between V2 and V2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges instance_actions functional tests.

Change-Id: I0773458cdeeca2f1eeac19d579cb8228769e1e18

commit_message:
Tests use common base class

By using a common base class, it's easy to (either permanently or
for testing) add a check that gets put on all Keystone tests.

Change-Id: I903d839a719ca49e7baea51756e13cc8ac2b0749

commit_message:
Correct cinder hacking check numbering

We have a couple of hacking checks that are specific to
Cinder that were written a while back.  Unfortunately, when
they were written the numbering scheme for hacking checks was
not understood.  We used N3xx when we should have used C3xx.

This patch corrects that mistake.

Change-Id: Ia17797005d444ab53a45b47b80b97799114001ee
Closes-bug: 1440833

commit_message:
execute: enforce C locale unless explicitly requested

A bug in our dnsmasq version checker [1] raised a question whether we
actually want to run any external services using locales that are
different from C. Assuming it's better to be safe than sorry, let's
enforce C locale.

Removed local LC_ALL setting for dnsmasq check since now it's global.

The patch allows execute() callers to override the new default by
passing 'LC_ALL' with their addl_env.

[1]: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/149524/

Related-Bug: #1412738
Change-Id: If6992f7a598743aaa87f6fe5ee4e1c5b2b32ccd4

The docs for the class constructor parameters for several
classes weren't rendered because they were on the __init__
method, which sphinx doesn't render. When the docs are generated
for the class the __init__ parameters are shown after the class

commit_message:
Generate docs for constructor

The docs for the class constructor parameters for several
classes weren't rendered because they were on the __init__
method, which sphinx doesn't render. When the docs are generated
for the class the __init__ parameters are shown after the class
name, so the parameters should be documented on the class where
they'll be rendered rather than on __init__.

Change-Id: I674ff76495aa4b30273083201f365bce790f447e

commit_message:
Sanity check after migration

Added a sanity_check call after the migration, so if a table in the
migration scripts is created not correctly the exception arise
before to go in production.

Closes-Bug: #1428065

commit_message:
Add database-server and database-server-ha.

This makes it possible to build controllers with either
MariaDB or Galera. The default is to use MariaDB, but
we can easily swap in Galera for CI (or as a default)
if needed too by using the database-server-ha element
instead.

Change-Id: I1654ae33709f77e187da6a12f6a58009ac79a39f

commit_message:
Share V2 and V2.1 hosts functional tests

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges all hosts functional tests.

Change-Id: Ibd53a7ddd4792942fe2dc45121dcc25fc9864903

commit_message:
Implements ETag for resource

This change implements ETag for resource.

This also changes the PATCH behavior to return the
modified resources, to be able to cache it.

Change-Id: I065efac876a6df52473dac5743e4b84f9ff6e509

commit_message:
Switch puppet job back to juno RDO repository

Dependencies are still being added to the kilo repository, so we are probably
better off on the more stable juno for the moment.

commit_message:
Add admin GW with metric for Neutron-enabled environments

It's required for nodes which are deployed before VIPs are up
and in case of multiple L2 segments.

Related-Bug: #1437842
Related-Bug: #1442078

Change-Id: Ib128ff4fab57bca34473e6ae25cd461c08133702

commit_message:
Allow sudo to determine neutron-rootwrap location

In some systems, setup.py may put neutron-rootwrap in some other path,
so let's just allow sudo and shell to locate it.

Change-Id: Ic2b5986436689cb3a71c1be560fba5971fea50f2

commit_message:
Fix db-sync dependencies

W/o this change, some config changes could
be not synced to db and neutron-server service
start not aligned with db sync process

The solution is to fix the dependencies for
Neutron_config stanzas before db sync exec
and for n-server service - after db sync

Closes-bug: #1384133

Change-Id: I769b6e7ddb567a21a91eeb77375213c131a3d396
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit d7c8d2327a0d46a79ca6519762f088efa8e7373a)

commit_message:
Make neutron_plugin_ml2 before db-sync

W/o this change some of config changes for
ml2 plugin could be not synced to db.

Solution is to add a notify on db-sync
for all Neutron_plugin_ml2 stanzas

Closes-bug: #1384119

Change-Id: I23f6bca99e1c077804011897814649419da326d4
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit 53688bf2b26682474427f31202756d3217ff20f5)

commit_message:
Remove UUIDs from RST pot files

We do not need the UUIDs for our toolchain, remove them.

They cause huge changes with each import with no benefit for us.

Note: Sphinx 1.3 by default disables UUID generation but we're using an
older Sphinx version for building, thus have to do this manually.

Change-Id: I3f3e910c5b2a2d03a3f04b67015526c3b7e77ddb

commit_message:
OpenStack Community Activity Report Q1 2015

  This report is produced quarterly to give Community Managers
  and OpenStack Foundation's management better insights on development
  activities and online conversations. The quantitative and qualitative
  assessment start from tracking actions across all OpenStack git
  repositories, gerrit code reviews, bug trackers as well as IRC channels,
  mailing lists and questions/answers.

Co-author: Stefano Maffulli
Change-Id: Ie3afdf0c8941d21896aa60dbf9d1cbd6593b5a7f

commit_message:
Specify network UUID for network create with cells

When the n-cell service is enabled, we create networks in both the
API cell and the child cell. Recent changes to tempest have tests
querying networks from the API and passing them for a server create.
In order for this to work in cells, the UUIDs for the network in
the API cell and the child cell must match, else the network won't
be found in the child.

This change adds the --uuid option to the nova-manage network create
command for cells only.

Related-Bug: #1441931

Depends-On: Ib29e632b09905f557a7a6910d58207ed91cdc047

Change-Id: Ib5933b1405c0761ff727e04cda0c502a826c8eaf

commit_message:
Merge certificates functional tests of v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges certificates functional tests.

Change-Id: I3439eb50bf5d64f2101681dc523def9c586f893d

commit_message:
Allow overriding ensure for glance-registry

The main glance class allows overriding the package_ensure setting
from the default of 'present', but on Debian based systems
glance-registry is a separate package.  This package updates the
glance::registry class to allow overriding the package ensure there
also.

Change-Id: I6182836728102e827f9d5a3beef4964dd6e8d7f9
(cherry picked from commit 9befc700a1b086b6f81fbb959a4c7520e83be5ad)

commit_message:
Removing python 2.6 support

Python 2.6 is no longer supported in Django >= 1.7 or by OpenStack
as of Kilo. Additionally, the versions of django_openstack_auth are
all capped on the stable branches, so this will not effect them.

Change-Id: I75fc4a0ba090eb0d10cda235a1deb75f734ab1c7

commit_message:
Fix API/Registry ensure for Ubuntu

On Ubuntu the API and Registry are separate packages so we need an
package_ensure for each.

Change-Id: I02dcca223f57392e7b4c82806a2c0d48d301d4aa

commit_message:
Removing py26 from django_openstack_auth in Kilo

django_openstack_auth needs to support newer versions of Django.
Starting Django 1.7, python 2.6 is no longer supported. Removing
python-26 jobs from django_openstack_auth gate for builds other
than Juno and Icehouse.

Change-Id: Ib9015e5020a86ece6a38eadb4d1a3900be29b139

commit_message:
Merge V2 and V2.1 Agent functional tests

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges Agent functional tests.

Change-Id: Ibfbe20f6c0b773ec7cf39d532074075c722deb63

commit_message:
Revert 'Remove image to local block device mapping'

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/153203/3 added check
for novaclient, removed the logic for both
--image and --block-device are added.

But actually the following valid boot command failed
due to the change here, so this patch reverted original
one and add some descriptions to avoid further removal.

nova boot test-vm --flavor m1.medium --image centos-vm-32
--nic net-id=c3f40e33-d535-4217-916b-1450b8cd3987
--block-device id=26b7b917-2794-452a-95e5-2efb2ca6e32d,bus=sata,
source=volume,bootindex=1

Change-Id: Ia29e63c72b34d3038aa591c466425e65edf5755b
Partial-Bug: #1433609

commit_message:
Make neutron_plugin_ml2 before db-sync

W/o this change some of config changes for
ml2 plugin could be not synced to db.

Solution is to add a notify on db-sync
for all Neutron_plugin_ml2 stanzas

Closes-bug: #1384119

Change-Id: I23f6bca99e1c077804011897814649419da326d4
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Allow overriding ensure for glance-registry

The main glance class allows overriding the package_ensure setting
from the default of 'present', but on Debian based systems
glance-registry is a separate package.  This package updates the
glance::registry class to allow overriding the package ensure there
also.

Change-Id: I6182836728102e827f9d5a3beef4964dd6e8d7f9

commit_message:
Notify services if swift.conf is modified

swift.conf contains the hash_suffix. With the current module, we have a
race condition where services can start *before* having the right hash
in swift.conf, so some objects mays be put in quarantine.

When usint swift_config (which affect swift.conf), we should restart all
services to ensure our ring is running correctly.

Change-Id: I1087ba4ec079ca9c43bea9ff0511347632871ec2
Closes-bug: #1442329
(cherry picked from commit 6dc85b0f7918fa295974f7afbb1a6b8a26f8f953)

commit_message:
Add serialization of context to FakeNotifier

Currently, the FakeNotifier doesn't do anything to check the context
that will be serialized when the RPC call is made. This change adds
a call to serialize the context to prevent bugs related to the
context passed in to send the notification.

Related-Bug: #1360911

Change-Id: I905f8421bc8e34c52b779d65a88d1ebf044f4dd1

(The function does not really start the transaction.)

The isolation level change would lead to the same deadlock issue set.'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-01-16 07:50:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

If the Transaction isolation level would be changed to 'READ-COMMITTED' by the other-commit. This commit effect is to eliminate the need for a try loop, without any side effect."}, {'account_id': 6788, 'date': '2015-01-16 14:00:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Attila, the FOR UPDATE lock has proved not to work as expected for example with Galera, see http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-May/035264.html that's why we are trying when possible to get rid of it in the code base. Your patch goes in the opposite direction, it reintroduces the lock. I think the problem you see could be fixed changing the isolation level of the transaction, using READ COMMITTED. With READ COMMITTED a process would get the current db view and if a concurrent process allocates the same segment, that would be seen. My suggestion is to change the isolation level of the transaction instead of locking. What do you think?"}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-01-16 16:22:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Interesting.., thanks for the link.

AFAIK The row level write lock will happen on 'UPDATE', the 'FOR UPDATE' just acquires the lock earlier. So it is not an additional lock.

What will the 'try update loop' strategy expected to do with two different galera writer node (Active-Active / Master-master) ?

Isn't 2th client gets a deadlock?

Can you confirm the 'FOR UPDATE' causes to `read-committed` as it does with `repeatable-read` even in multiple active galare writer setup?

Indeed the galera is popular, but on the 'ops session' actually how many user used multiple active writer ?"}, {'account_id': 2035, 'date': '2015-01-16 18:49:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Echoing Rossella, it's not just Galera that is driving us to remove 'FOR UPDATE'.  Locking is an anti-pattern when it comes to scalability, and we need to minimize its use as much as possible.

A patch recently merged that makes it trivial to change the isolation level [1], and I would encourage you to see whether you can use that capability to good effect.  As per the mysql docs [2], it is possible to change the isolation level in the middle of a transaction: 

"Any session is free to change its session isolation level (even in the middle of a transaction), or the isolation level for its next transaction."

1: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/129288/
2: http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.0/en/set-transaction.html'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-01-18 07:33:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The full sentence:
"A change to the global default isolation level requires the SUPER privilege. Any session is free to change its session isolation level (even in the middle of a transaction), or the isolation level for its next transaction."

You missed the "for its next transaction." part, it does not have effect to an already started transaction. (You can try it, in a terminal)

For this operation any hard coded number of retry limit is bad design!

By locking the row earlier, the concurrent processes and the db thread does not wastes CPU cycles on trying something what will fail at the end.

The 'For Update' just prevents concurrent write on the given row and does not prevents any other operation, since we do 'for update' on the same number of row as we do 'UPDATE' we do not spend more resources for managing any additional locks.'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-01-18 19:22:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I did some testing (with go):

"Any session is free to change its session isolation level (even in the middle of a transaction), OR the isolation level for its next transaction." (emphasis mine)

In contradiction to your reading, mysql does support changing the session isolation level in the middle of a transaction.  The patch I referenced requires this capability and does have the desired effect, so I'm not sure what you're running into in your experiment.

Also, the goal is not to change the global level, only the session one, so special permissions are not required.'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-01-19 05:36:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

In this case the 'FOR UPDATE' way has better throughput, and the try/update/count way has less retry, but it reaches more than 10 retry at 3 thread."}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-01-19 08:20:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

- check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-full-2 http://logs.openstack.org/40/147540/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-full-2/5d04975/ : SUCCESS in 54m 53s

- check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-dvr http://logs.openstack.org/40/147540/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-dvr/1d975dc/ : FAILURE in 35m 13s (non-voting)
- gate-neutron-pylint http://logs.openstack.org/40/147540/1/check/gate-neutron-pylint/c76fa41/ : SUCCESS in 5m 34s'}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2015-02-13 12:23:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

That's not the way it should be done, it's just not scalable.
I wonder how various discussions has lead you to the idea of bringing back SELECT FOR UPDATE."}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2015-02-13 15:00:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I finally understand where Attila's interest in locking queries is coming from! I did not notice this bug and patch before.

While analogies with mutexes, futexes, and spinlocks are very interesting (see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/100963 for more).

I think Attila has the right root cause for the bug. Quoting him:
"The method tries to retry the allocation, but instead of trying a
different segment it tries with same segment id multiple times"

SELECT FOR UPDATE solves this problem with the exception of active/active clusters such as MySQL Galera. For this kind of deployment this behaviour is likely to result in failed data set certification which then manifests as a deadlock. But this has been discussed enough already in reviews and on the mailing list.

In my opinion the issue with the current patch is that it's relying on a model of the world where isolation is read commited. I would not be surprised if the fault you're trying to fix never manifests on postregres with the default settings. It is my opinion that developers should never rely on the fact that the backend provides or not a given isolation level, but we're not here for debating opinions.
As I read in this review about changing transaction's isolation level or even about changing the isolation level within a transaction (is that even possible?) I merely want to point out that I think this might be a recipe for further instability and maintainability chaos.

Coming back to this specific bug, I wonder it the bug itself would manifest is each retry was executed in a different transaction. This is something that I missed while reviewing the patch that introduced this (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/71904/25/neutron/plugins/ml2/drivers/type_vlan.py). By the way, please note that patch #71904 pretty much replaced the select...for update you're reinstating here.

I saw that Attila has already done a lot of experiments. It seems his results lean in favour of select...for update, but the active/active restriction is, possibly, a deal breaker.
So I also wonder if these 2 alternatives has been considered:

A - change this transaction (and there are similars for vxlan I believe), with a two step process.

Step1. Query for non-allocated ids

Step2. Begin transaction. Pop record from select query. Update to allocate=True with CAS-style query. Commit if 1 record was updated, abort and retry otherwise.

The select query is basically executed in another transaction, and it might have stale records when the isolation level is repeatable read or serializable. This might result in more failures in the update query, but since you pop a different record every time the number of retries should be limited.

B - Leverage the fact that we know how many workers are out there, and we (should) know also the size allocation space.
In this we would partition allocation ID among workers so that no clashes are possible.
For instance if we have 4 workers, worker 0 will have ids whose modulo 4 is 0, worker 1 those whose modulo 4 is 1, and so on.

The Caveat for A is that I believe there is a risk of starvation if the API server is pelted with non-bulk allocation requests. Basically one prtocess might give up retrying because some other process always takes the id it chose.
The Caveat for B is obviously that we have no way so far to identify the current worker from neutron's application code.

Sorry for this long response, I hope you find it helpful for the discussion'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2015-02-13 20:46:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

perhaps the 2nd strategy I proposed will also become more complex if we consider that every worker can have multiple greenthreads.'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-02-16 11:03:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Salvatore: You can read here why the 'FOR UPDATE' is working in a multi-writer setup https://review.openstack.org/#/c/149261/.

Yes, an isolation level change could make this working in non galera setup, but not sufficient for supporting the multi-writer setup.

For me the 'FOR UPDATE' performed better then the isolation level change.

Yes, the partitioning the usual trick, but doing it properly in this case is really complex.

I tried a randomized approach, it helped with the isolation level change (READ COMITED), but the 'FOR UPDATE' was faster after I added the missing index.
The randomized approach also has higher chance to cause regular DBDeadlock. 

For me a little bit surprising an application does not uses the same isolation settings an all DB backed.
Usually if an application designed for a higher isolation level, it has issues with a lower one. It may explain why we saw more gate failures with pg, even if it's driver does not blocks in a native code."}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-02-17 16:28:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-02-25 00:54:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Salvatore you don't need to select and then update - a single query could update the first available and then we can read-back the assigned row. The query would either:
 - succeed (1 row updated)
 - succeed (no rows updated)
 - fail (deadlock)

See Julien's comments on Jaypipes blog post for an example query."}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2015-02-25 08:00:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Robert, I guess that you're right in this case we can just run a single update query for any available VNI and deal with deadlocks or no row updated issues."}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-02-25 21:15:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The read-back approach requires to use the network id instead of a boolean in the allocation tables.

It is also one write lock, the end result expected to be similar to the FOR UPDATE way.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-13 01:39:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-04-10 14:13:26.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]
