[{'created': '2015-01-15 14:53:45.000000000', 'message': "Use 'FOR UPDATE' in allocate_partially_specified_segment

The allocate_partially_specified_segment fails to allocate
a segment if a concurrent process already allocated it.

The method tries to retry the allocation, but instead of trying a
different segment it tries with same segment id multiple times.

The issue could be addressed by iterating over the first select result
set instead of reissuing the same select on old database view, in this
case the retry limit should not be a hard-coded (10) and we should consume
the full result set before give up.

The 'FOR UPDATE' way does not affected by the `old database view` issue,
it can be applied without a retry loop.

The deadlock free allocation on bulk allocation cannot
be guaranteed without ensuring all allocator in all process
uses the same ordering.

Instead of pretending it easily can be done, extending the method
documentation with a possible DBDeadlock exception.

Change-Id: I58837fd132ffaa9d443137b5fc100ac9fc9caabb
Closes-Bug: #1410854
"}]
commit_message:
Use 'FOR UPDATE' in allocate_partially_specified_segment

The allocate_partially_specified_segment fails to allocate
a segment if a concurrent process already allocated it.

The method tries to retry the allocation, but instead of trying a
different segment it tries with same segment id multiple times.

The issue could be addressed by iterating over the first select result
set instead of reissuing the same select on old database view, in this
case the retry limit should not be a hard-coded (10) and we should consume
the full result set before give up.

The 'FOR UPDATE' way does not affected by the `old database view` issue,
it can be applied without a retry loop.

The deadlock free allocation on bulk allocation cannot
be guaranteed without ensuring all allocator in all process
uses the same ordering.

Instead of pretending it easily can be done, extending the method
documentation with a possible DBDeadlock exception.

Change-Id: I58837fd132ffaa9d443137b5fc100ac9fc9caabb
Closes-Bug: #1410854

commit_message:
Fix the unicode encode error when create volume

Using six.text_type(value) to set image_name to
avoid UnicodeEncodeError.

Change-Id: I30542df18f31a3e07cb4b9a61521ebded62ffbc4
Closes-Bug: #1426203

commit_message:
Forbid the user to specify custom ports during creating docker-apps

At the moment there is no mechanism to change container port for
application. Thus, we shouldn't allow the user to specify custom
ports apart from cases when application requires explicit network
configuration and ports must be specified as environment variables

Change-Id: I9382478765d6b40142b3723e0bed050d48f1da4a
Closes-Bug: #1442154

commit_message:
exc_filters: support for ForeignKey error on delete

The current code only supports this type of constraint on INSERT, this
adds support for DELETE.

Change-Id: I981eb5f7b71bd37a35a93bbd3fada01d74aba12d
Closes-Bug: #1439358

commit_message:
Add pyngus to requirements

oslo.messaging use pyngus for the one of its functionnal job (amqp1).

This python module is not in the requirement of oslo.messaging
because it can't be build on ubuntu trusty due to a missing c library
qpid-proton, and because the driver is experimental and can be run only
on fedora >= 21 for now, so the installation of it have been hardcoded
in devstack for fedora to allow gating on this driver.

Since all python modules installed via pip are now checked against
global-requirements we must have this deps here.

This change does that.

Closes-bug: #1442488

Change-Id: I91a7655becc4d559e3928b67cf70586cdaf42a29

commit_message:
Move entry points for plugin agents into neutron.cmd.eventlet

This patch moves entry points for the following plugins:

- bigswitch
- cisco
- hyperv
- ibm
- linuxbridge
- nec
- oneconvergence
- openvswitch
- sriovnicagent

This allows us to remove explicit monkey_patch() call.

Also removed ability to execute agents from the tree without utilizing
entry points since it's not supported.

Related-Bug: #1418541
Change-Id: I2a57e4f497f33306dda1060f6dce5458e3ba68fa

[{'created': '2015-04-10 13:24:05.000000000', 'message': "Update ssh module version

The ssh module had an issue with hostkeys on RHEL systems prior to
version 2.4.0 that would cause puppet to error during a run: the
sshdsakey fact returns empty, so the exported dsa sshkey resource fails
due to an empty parameter[1]. The current dependency restricts the ssh
module to less than 2.0, which contains the bug.

Problematically, version 2.5.0 of the ssh module adds a change that is
incompatible with older 3.x versions of puppet [2], which breaks our tests.

This patch updates the ssh dependency to use full range of the next
major version in order to be as accomodating as possible. However, for
RHEL users to avoid the ssh key bug, they must use at least version
2.4.0. For users of older puppet versions to avoid the bad parameter
issue, they must use a version less than 2.5.0. The .fixtures.yml pins
to 2.4.0 for maximum compatibility. We could pin the dependency in the
metadata to exactly 2.4.0 as well, but since these are issues in the
ssh module, not swift's use of the ssh module, it is more appropriate
just to allow the newer version but not be too restrictive on the
version.

The ssh::server class has an API change between 1.x and 2.x, but the
new parameters (ensure, storeconfigs_enabled, and an options hash) have
acceptable defaults.

[1] https://github.com/saz/puppet-ssh/blob/v1.4.0/manifests/hostkeys.pp#L8
[2] https://github.com/saz/puppet-ssh/blob/v2.5.0/manifests/server/install.pp#L7

commit_message:
Update ssh module version

The ssh module had an issue with hostkeys on RHEL systems prior to
version 2.4.0 that would cause puppet to error during a run: the
sshdsakey fact returns empty, so the exported dsa sshkey resource fails
due to an empty parameter[1]. The current dependency restricts the ssh
module to less than 2.0, which contains the bug.

Problematically, version 2.5.0 of the ssh module adds a change that is
incompatible with older 3.x versions of puppet [2], which breaks our tests.

This patch updates the ssh dependency to use full range of the next
major version in order to be as accomodating as possible. However, for
RHEL users to avoid the ssh key bug, they must use at least version
2.4.0. For users of older puppet versions to avoid the bad parameter
issue, they must use a version less than 2.5.0. The .fixtures.yml pins
to 2.4.0 for maximum compatibility. We could pin the dependency in the
metadata to exactly 2.4.0 as well, but since these are issues in the
ssh module, not swift's use of the ssh module, it is more appropriate
just to allow the newer version but not be too restrictive on the
version.

The ssh::server class has an API change between 1.x and 2.x, but the
new parameters (ensure, storeconfigs_enabled, and an options hash) have
acceptable defaults.

[1] https://github.com/saz/puppet-ssh/blob/v1.4.0/manifests/hostkeys.pp#L8
[2] https://github.com/saz/puppet-ssh/blob/v2.5.0/manifests/server/install.pp#L7

Change-Id: I30216b0336b5f1f1c65e711cb97654ef663ba01f
(cherry picked from commit 7ad2a10e1fd5f78a6632cf76c8def3ae4559677e)

commit_message:
Update ssh module version

The ssh module had an issue with hostkeys on RHEL systems prior to
version 2.4.0 that would cause puppet to error during a run: the
sshdsakey fact returns empty, so the exported dsa sshkey resource fails
due to an empty parameter[1]. The current dependency restricts the ssh
module to less than 2.0, which contains the bug.

Problematically, version 2.5.0 of the ssh module adds a change that is
incompatible with older 3.x versions of puppet [2], which breaks our tests.

This patch updates the ssh dependency to use full range of the next
major version in order to be as accomodating as possible. However, for
RHEL users to avoid the ssh key bug, they must use at least version
2.4.0. For users of older puppet versions to avoid the bad parameter
issue, they must use a version less than 2.5.0. The .fixtures.yml pins
to 2.4.0 for maximum compatibility. We could pin the dependency in the
metadata to exactly 2.4.0 as well, but since these are issues in the
ssh module, not swift's use of the ssh module, it is more appropriate
just to allow the newer version but not be too restrictive on the
version.

The ssh::server class has an API change between 1.x and 2.x, but the
new parameters (ensure, storeconfigs_enabled, and an options hash) have
acceptable defaults.

[1] https://github.com/saz/puppet-ssh/blob/v1.4.0/manifests/hostkeys.pp#L8
[2] https://github.com/saz/puppet-ssh/blob/v2.5.0/manifests/server/install.pp#L7

Change-Id: I30216b0336b5f1f1c65e711cb97654ef663ba01f

commit_message:
Handle nova-network tuple format in legacy RPC calls

The NetworkRequestList object renders tuples differently depending on
network manager. When falling back to older RPC APIs we are missing
the special casing for the nova network, causing things to blow
up during icehouse->juno partial upgrades when specifying a network
with during instance spawn.

Change-Id: I792f64aa5cbbe9666505d1c7958796c771d4aff2
Closes-bug: #1438920

commit_message:
Add logging to dangling port to ml2 delete_subnet

This is useful when trouble shooting test failures.
Also, in db_base_plugin_v2, log only port_id instead of
full allocation object.

Change-Id: I3d77318aee70836de125687a7f6c0f495d545f21
Related-Bug: #1357055

I'd like to know if there are compelling reasons doing that?

A resource type's support status will evolve like this, IIUC:

PROTOTYPE -> SUPPORTED -> DEPRECATED -> UNSUPPORTED

I do agree that for support status changes, we need to attach a version number, so it becomes something like this?

status    since

commit_message:
Add version to support_status where it omitted

This improve doc notes about deprecated objects
and adds option 'version' to all objects with
support_status parameter.

blueprint deprecating-improvements

Change-Id: I82f9f4514142a3a66c872722b265fee365eb5de2

commit_message:
Make sure snapshot belongs to stack for actions

Check the snapshot belongs to stack when deleting and showing
stack's snapshot, and restoring from snapshot.

Change-Id: I8ce170b40b05ae17669524d75f80e06e39986673
Closes-Bug: #1437602

commit_message:
Ensure Replication Tests do not use a stale token

Fixed the replication tests to re-authenticate the common test dbaas
client in order to ensure that we do not use a stale auth_token when
running the replication tests.

Change-Id: I37a2a4b7dca056e84b48c66cbe3b8c8fb6a2f1db
Closes-bug: 1394831
(cherry picked from commit 500613e68f365596dcec4c0466978be409be99ee)

commit_message:
Avoid re-using the same timeout for further watcher ops

Instead of re-using the same timeout that is passed into the
'run_watchers' function we should adjust that timeout after
each fetch so that the expected timeout the user gives to this
function is observed.

Change-Id: I5d171b1ac8b207213224f4e0f3909625de7275db
(cherry picked from commit e38a29f67180cb40a0b7915305bec62ed9527229)

commit_message:
Notify services if swift.conf is modified

swift.conf contains the hash_suffix. With the current module, we have a
race condition where services can start *before* having the right hash
in swift.conf, so some objects mays be put in quarantine.

When usint swift_config (which affect swift.conf), we should restart all
services to ensure our ring is running correctly.

Change-Id: I1087ba4ec079ca9c43bea9ff0511347632871ec2
Closes-bug: #1442329

* mention Ironic inspection

commit_message:
provide explicit defaults for boolean values

When creating a neutron_network resource without explicitly setting the
router_external parameter, the network would be created with
router:external=True, which would result in a network to which it was
not possible to attach nova instances.

This change sets explicit defaults for all boolean options in the
neutron_network type.

Closes-bug: 1436133
Change-Id: Id0f950da791c65ba9034046177870f31f6f57c46

commit_message:
Do not fail if some images were not provisioned

It is adding fault tolerance for image based provision method.
Also all test were changed to use image based provision method.

Change-Id: Id933fc589b132ccb09487b2924b49efd3f714148
Closes-bug:  1438844

commit_message:
Add pypi download + version badges

Also makes the docs look more like the other
oslo libraries so that the content is easily readable
across projects.

Change-Id: I7b048bc4425197f87436281dd5e46619390c3f43

commit_message:
neutron: make l3/vpn agent use config-dir

Now that advanced services are split from the core tree, there are no
guarantees that any auxiliary configuration files are installed on the
system.

In devstack, it's handled by dynamically generating list of CLI
arguments based on which services are enabled in local.conf. This
approach is not applicable for distributions though where those
arguments are usually hardcoded in a service manifest.

Distributions will need to switch to using an approach that is more
dynamic. oslo.config provides us with an option to replace --config-file
arguments with --config-dir, that would load all *.conf files from
there. That would allow distributions to keep the same arguments no
matter which services are installed on a system.

This patch applies the same approach to devstack installations since
it's expected to be the way to go forward.

In this patch, I'm assuming that VPN agent cannot be used on the same
node as L3 agent. If that's not the case, we may need to maintain two
separate conf-dirs.

Note: we're leaving actual configuration files in their old paths, we
only create symbolic links to point to them from the configuration
directory.

Closes-Bug: #1431292
Depends-On: I072f35100737f4f139f647b508a22b45d40f13fc
Change-Id: I84fc20c4b6f58c2ae75bb1be226dcd783f81832e

Not sure I entirely grasp the rationale behind this fix. I understand that neither devstack nor grenade need to worry about the hard-coded list of config files (as it's generated on the fly based on the available services), so what are we aiming to do here? That said, I can see that the level of indirection makes you solve the problem for a packager/deployer, but is this the right place to fix the issue?

Ultimately we want to guarantee that Neutron services can understand the config-dir option, but doing it here seems an abuse.

Perhaps the rationale here is not so much distro needs per se, but the fact that we'd want to consolidate the config management. This was a topic handled multiple times on the ML, but I am not sure we ever reached consensus. For this reason, I wouldn't want this change to fly under the radar.

I support the consolidation of config files, but I don't think symlinking existing files is a sound approach."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-03-13 14:17:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

Armando, you're probably correct, there is more for the issue than the immediate l3 agent need, and consolidation is the way to go. It won't be simple, since we'll need to maintain backwards compatibility with existing files (hence symlinks).

Maybe for neutron, we should just switch to new config directories without symbolic links, and distributions may handle compatibility problems by maintain configuration files in both places for some number of cycling, to finally drop the old --config-file path. That said, it's really beyond devstack interest, so probably should not go in (marking with WIP-1 both patches for now)."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-09 16:16:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

neutron: generate config-dir for L3/VPN agent

Fill in the directory with symbolic links to enabled configuration
values, so that devstack can use --config-dir= argument instead of
multiple --config-file arguments when starting L3/VPN agent.

Note that the change is not mandatory for all distributions, so no
specific release notes are required. Distributions can mimic the
approach that we take with the patch in their service manifests on their
own schedule.

Change-Id: I072f35100737f4f139f647b508a22b45d40f13fc
Closes-Bug: #1431292

commit_message:
Cluster vcenter compatibility fix

Upgrades cluster attributes from 6.0 to 6.1 with
use_vcenter option and fixes creating vmware attributes
only for releases which support it.

Closes-Bug: #1439602
Change-Id: I2fa90e76aee98bd35cd9250700812844fd2e5850

Excuse my ignorance, but can't/won't the concerns about atomicity be handled by containing the "make a new revision" operation in a transaction? If not, why not?'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2015-04-01 13:01:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2015-04-01 13:13:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@cdent: 

this due to the fact that we can patch a resource, so we have to get the not patched attributes from the previous revision of the resource, and to complicate a bit the thing, the resource attributes are dispatched into two tables.

Also, 'select' then 'insert (with some value from previous) (in two statements) is not safe even within one transaction.

My previous version of the patch was using the 'revision' to track and reject concurrency update of a resource.

The latest patchset use 'insert from .. select' statement that is safe (because that lock the table until the transaction is committed) and allow concurrency updated of a resource attributes."}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2015-04-01 18:27:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Keep history of updated resource attributes

This change keeps history of updated resource attributes
by creating a new row in resource_history tables each time the
resource table is updated.

Each resource extension table also gains a '<resource_name>_history' to
track its history too.

Change-Id: If532b5167f0bbecb94f15594f0227c537ed26f77

commit_message:
Handle CHECK constraint integrity in PostgreSQL

PostgreSQL offers CHECK constraints integrity which are currently raised
as generic error. This patch add a filter so they can have their own
exception type.

Change-Id: I7e36ef4385b227d1e62e18277d470047a369a238

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-09 14:51:21.000000000', 'message': "Add filters for DBDataError exception

We currently don't distinguish DB errors, that are due to problems
with the processed data (like division by zero, numeric value out
of range, incorrect data type passed, etc)

This actually led to a problem when MySQL threw two different errors
depending on the randomly generated UUID value and we wrapped only
one of those cases properly, which caused the test case to fail time
to time in the gate.

Closes-Bug: #1442178

Change-Id: I02891f3b1ede6f33834e5637be43496499cc88e7
"}]
commit_message:
Add filters for DBDataError exception

We currently don't distinguish DB errors, that are due to problems
with the processed data (like division by zero, numeric value out
of range, incorrect data type passed, etc)

This actually led to a problem when MySQL threw two different errors
depending on the randomly generated UUID value and we wrapped only
one of those cases properly, which caused the test case to fail time
to time in the gate.

Closes-Bug: #1442178

Change-Id: I02891f3b1ede6f33834e5637be43496499cc88e7

'}, {'created': '2013-11-21 16:10:23.000000000', 'message': "Remove mute_weight_value option on mute child weigher

With weight normalization it is not needed anymore to inflate the
weights so that one weiger can win, since this can be made just by
adjusting the multiplier. This change does not break backwards
compatibility, since the multiplier has been also increased so that it
actually mutes the other weighers.

Implements blueprint normalize-scheduler-weights
DocImpact: The mute_weight_value has been removed so the operators need
to adjust the mute_weight_multiplier to a proper value if they weren't
using the defaults.

"}, {'created': '2014-08-22 07:06:18.000000000', 'message': "Remove mute_weight_value option on mute child weigher

The nova.cells.weights.mute_child.MuteChildWeigher used a large
mute_weight_value flag to inflate the weigher's value. This was needed
before weight normalization was in place, so that the weigher could win
against other weighers. Now, with weight normalization in place this is
not neededanymore, since the maximum value that a weigher would take will
be 1.0 (weights are normalized between 0.0 and 1.0). We should use the
multiplier to get the same behavior (i.e. make the weigher prevail
against other weighers), the multiplier has been also increased so
that it actually mutes the other weighers an does not break backwards
compatibility.

commit_message:
Scheduler: deprecate mute_weight_value option on weigher

The nova.cells.weights.mute_child.MuteChildWeigher used a large
mute_weight_value flag to inflate the weigher's value. This was needed
before weight normalization was in place, so that the weigher could win
against other weighers. Now, with weight normalization in place this is
not needed any more, since the maximum value that a weigher would take will
be 1.0 (weights are normalized between 0.0 and 1.0). We should use the
multiplier to get the same behavior (i.e. make the weigher prevail
against other weighers), the multiplier has been also increased so
that it actually mutes the other weighers an does not break backwards
compatibility.

DocImpact: The mute_weight_value has been marked as deprecated so the
operators need to adjust the mute_weight_multiplier to a proper value if
they weren't using the defaults.

Closes-Bug: #1340068
Change-Id: Idebd7649909567034b01ce04416ce315fb936b17

commit_message:
limit alarm actions

Currently we have alarm quotas, but user still can create a single
alarm with thousands of actions, the worse thing is that normal
user can create log:// and test:// notifiers which they could never
use it, but by doing such thing, normal user can break down ceilometer
services, then maybe the whole server. That is because log:// will
log to local disk (by default) and test:// will continuously consume
server's memory.

This patch adds a configure option to let cloud administrator to
limit each alarm's maximum actions for three states, and disables
normal user to create log:// and test:// to avoid bad things happen.

Change-Id: I7325ab72c94d307075f1317ee0b7b19f30a5d231
Closes-Bug: #1408248
DocImpact

commit_message:
libvirt: reuse unfilter_instance pass-through method

The libvirt driver already has an unfilter_instance() method that calls
firewall_driver.unfilter_instance().

This change updates a couple of other places in the driver that are
calling firewall_driver.unfilter_instance() directly to use the
pass-through method.

Change-Id: I93dc9415e0c7e2a0b9e400bcb564b1a6256c9032

commit_message:
Forbid setting is_public via querystring

All package parameters are specified via json body.
Before there was an undocumented ability to set 'is_public' via
querystring. This patch removes this exception and updates respective
tests

Change-Id: Idb284ca1af2902abcc19da112da9024bbbd28fc6
Closes-Bug: #1441125

Open Liberty development

Bump pre-version in setup.cfg to formally open Liberty development.
Kilo release branch will be cut from the previous commit.

commit_message:
Added support for Nova Network

Nova-Network mode is assumes when no 'network' service is
registered in Keystone

Floating IP addresses are taken from default pool ('public')

Change-Id: I6f4b7908bd4bbcd375f64705c7dd06e3954f1ec7

In my quick test, it seems to be working my laptops SAIO environment. 

However you need to add the new option to deployment guide and I'd make sure it's clearly stated in the documentation and maybe in the sample configuration that swift will not delete objects, and drives will fill up much faster unless something is done to delete at the users deleted retention period.

I know it's WIP and an interesting idea Christian.. just my 2 initial cents :)"}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2015-01-07 07:31:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thanks Matthew for your feedback!

Yes, documentation update is mandatory; I wanted to get some initial feedback first to see if there is a chance to get something like this into Swift upstream. I will enhance this patch if there is some interest for this.

Worst case with a 24h expiration would be a 50% overhead in disk usage - but this would only be true if all objects in the cluster are deleted every 24hrs. Most likely this is not the case. There is also only a single copy kept (the last version). Of course you can combine this with object versioning too...

commit_message:
WIP: Low-level object undelete functionality

WIP: for discussion, needs some documentation updates too.

Currently each object DELETE is executed immediately, making it hard to
impossible to recover from unintentional object deletes. As an operator I would
like have a more failsafe approach to this, for example to undelete objects in a
short period of time after deletion. This might be useful to recover from
external application bugs or abused authentication credentials.

This patch adds a new configuration option to etc/swift.conf making it possible
to change the default behavior. If keep-deleted-object is set to True each
object deletion is not unlinking the object file directly, but moving it to a
"deleted_objects" directory on the disk. This makes the operation fast (it is
basically only a rename), and these files are not handled anymore by internal
Swift processes. This also means that these deleted object files are no longer
replicated or audited.

Note that only the last object .data and .meta file is kept, this patch
explicitly does not keep multiple versions of the same object.

Operators need to remove older files files frequently, for example using a
command like this:

find -L /srv/ -type f -name "*.deleted" -mtime +24 -exec rm {} \;

Object undeletion has to be done manually with this patch; however it is quite
easy to add a more sophisticated approach as an additional object server
middleware later.

Change-Id: If03adc8d73455b1b3b213a694b894b0ba9c5ece1

commit_message:
Add hacking check for print() statements

We are frequently having to -1 patches because people
forget print() statements that were used for debug in
their development.  Can save everyone time and trouble by
adding this simple hacking check.

The check excluded the cinder/cmd directory as the files in there
legitimately need to use the print() command.  Also wsgi.py and
the test_hds_nas_backend.py files make use of print, so I have
excluded those from checking as well.

Change-Id: I2066eeb2bdc6c9af294d0b9befb7e0b32abd1378

The call to get_subnet_ids_on_router can return an empty list.
If the subnet_ids list is empty, the subsequent call to get
the ports on a subnet returns all ports.  If this occurs
when doing a remove_router_interface, the performance
of a remove_router_interface degrades significantly.  This change
returns immediately from check_ports_exist_on_l3agents if no

commit_message:
Return from check_ports_exist_on_l3agent if no subnet found

The call to get_subnet_ids_on_router can return an empty list.
If the subnet_ids list is empty, the subsequent call to get
the ports on a subnet returns all ports.  If this occurs
when doing a remove_router_interface, the performance
of a remove_router_interface degrades significantly.  This change
returns immediately from check_ports_exist_on_l3agents if no
subnet is found.  A new unit test has been added to cover
the specific case of returning immediately without calling
get_ports when a remove_router_interface operation is performed.

This allows the DVR job on stable/juno to go back to normal.

Conflicts:
        neutron/tests/unit/test_l3_schedulers.py

Change-Id: I247d3bae152ab4f8ab7e00bd24d878eb08dca1ba
Closes-Bug: #1420032
Depends-On: I15bbf16fd4378c6431e9da8942d0968e7a012a91
(cherry picked from commit 760fe6a8fabc921e75367b5f02bab4fc326b8115)

commit_message:
update cinder-vmware tests

There was checkbox "Cinder" on VMware tab which was removed on
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/169830/ and deployment serializer
was changed on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171575/.

In patch set 6, i have updated the blueprint to be generic enough for all hypervisors and made as specific to glance file system image store.'}, {'account_id': 12898, 'date': '2014-12-12 08:27:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2014-12-12 18:42:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-12-22 15:06:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

Kanagaraj, I completely see that streaming images through the Glance API server is a performance bottleneck. However, I really do think that we should direct all efforts towards the glance.store library integration to solve this problem. We actually do *not* want to continue using the nova/image/download/* modules because they are a hack and are not the "future" of image byte-streamining operations in Nova. Instead, the glance.store library is the future.

I'd like you to work with Flavio Percoco on this blueprint:

https://github.com/openstack/nova-specs/blob/master/specs/kilo/approved/remove-glanceclient-wrapper.rst

That sums up the direction we're trying to go with regards to utilizing the image locations properties to have virt driver code be able to stream image bytes directly from backend data stores without needing to go through the Glance API server.

Best,

-jay'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-12-22 19:09:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-2

What Jay said'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-04-10 09:37:13.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

This has not been worked on for a while. Please restore the change if you want to keep working on it, and move it into liberty.'}]

commit_message:
nova boot optimization using NFS glance image store

This blueprint enables nova to optimize the instance
boot process by using NFS with glance file system
based image store and all hypervisors.

Change-Id: Ia9244cd53dd43af7b7777aa994a4e99b5ca95150

commit_message:
Log Request ID Mappings

Tracking requests across multiple OpenStack services is difficult.
This is a proposal for logging corresponding request IDs together, so users
can easily lookup the request IDs of services other than the one the user
called directly.

blueprint log-request-id-mappings

Change-Id: Ie0089fa5006c7dc2b81a2bc3700b8728ed9700f6
Previously-approved: juno

commit_message:
Introduce Pacemaker driver for the servicegroup.

Apart of providing servicegroup information just like the other drivers, it'll

VMT-snapshot) to boot up multiple homogeneous VMs.This will reduce boot-up
data transfer and accelerate the boot-up process.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-07 13:33:46.000000000', 'message': "Do not re-elect RabbitMQ multistate resource master

Current monitor action for multistate RabbitMQ resource
in Pacemaker  may re-elect existing master when there is
no need to do so. That is a problem as master elections
introduce full cluster downtime and we don't want
additional elections.

The fix is to check whether the given node uptime is equal
to the other nodes uptime and drop this node from the list
of candidates if there is a master exists. Note, there is a
special 'rabbit-master' attribute in CIB for this.

Closes-bug: #1435254

Change-Id: I6f2484fb8f3284f76461c184148d27aa86a5d4b6
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
"}]
commit_message:
Do not re-elect RabbitMQ multistate resource master

Current monitor action for multistate RabbitMQ resource
in Pacemaker  may re-elect existing master when there is
no need to do so. That is a problem as master elections
introduce full cluster downtime and we don't want
additional elections.

The fix is to check whether the given node uptime is equal
to the other nodes uptime and drop this node from the list
of candidates if there is a master exists. Note, there is a
special 'rabbit-master' attribute in CIB for this.

Closes-bug: #1435254

Change-Id: I6f2484fb8f3284f76461c184148d27aa86a5d4b6
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Blueprint for re-adding the coverage extension

This spec proposes reviving the previously removed coverage extension.
This will allow for collecting coverage from tempest runs or any other
api consumer.

Spec for blueprint coverage-extension
Previously-approved and implemented: Grizzly

Change-Id: I2bf0e3294bd30645f60b72481b55fbb1a131a3b2

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-12-05 00:55:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

This sounds like it's bordering on providing more information via nova than I think we want. IMHO, if the nova-compute service is alive on the host, then we should report that the host is up. If it's not, then it doesn't matter if it's up, down, or purple, from nova's perspective.

Actual host alive-ness should be monitored by a tool responsible for doing that, right? Am I missing how this actually provides more nova-relevant information?"}, {'account_id': 13692, 'date': '2014-12-05 12:21:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

If nova is the brain which provide information to other part of the stack about certain thing, I think it has to be accurate. Decision based on inaccurate information may cause data inconsistency on other part of the stack (the example is the bug report, which I've linked in the BP), or just make the user confused (on Horizon "compute host" is an ambiguous term).

Please, bear in mind, that this blueprint address only the way to expose such information. Currently I'm working on the other one, with the proposal to utilize Pacemaker to provide reliable information (and fencing in the same time).'}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2014-12-09 18:34:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

(2 comments)

What information is Nova providing that's inaccurate?  The servicegroup API indicates whether or not the nova-compute service has checked in recently, nothing more.  It's not making a statement about the health of the host."}, {'account_id': 13692, 'date': '2014-12-10 07:46:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 13692, 'date': '2014-12-10 10:06:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

In Horizon there is a hypervisor/compute host tab, which provide the information about *host* based on *compute service* from service groups. I know, that this might be Horizon issue, but currently host state is not exposed by any service.

Nova have command 'nova evacuate' which underneath check the host state using servicegroup api.

Nova also have a command 'nova host-list' which actually does use servicegroup to list the hosts - which may be misleading, since command (nova service-list) is doing almost the same thing, but much more verbose - in a way that from user perspective 'nova host-list' is just a subset for 'nova service-list'."}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2014-12-10 17:58:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 13692, 'date': '2014-12-11 06:41:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Propose for new way of check for the host condition.

Instead of compute service existence check, new type of check for host state
is introduced.

APIImpact

Change-Id: I3a3b999233d6220862f07f7e780ef0eef73b3599

I'm primarily an OS operator.  As such, we have the same problem with orphans (mainly when someone deletes a project but does not first delete any VMs in that project.)

So I agree this is a problem that should be addressed.  This approach feels like a band-aid, rather than a complete solution, though.  While it would be great to have reporting/alerting on orphans... it would be even better to address the orphan problem itself, so that orphans are no longer created.

Still in favor of this change as written, but ultimately would like to see a "final solution to the orphan problem."'}, {'account_id': 11531, 'date': '2014-12-03 07:31:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Support the detection and alarm of orphans

In existing OpenStack cluster, there are some orphans on many compute node,
these orphans consumes a lot of resources, but the OpenStack can not manage
these orphans, and also can't timely detection and notify the user to clean up,
so I think that the nova should be able to manage these orphans, and can notify
the admin or user to process it.

Change-Id: I935aff27d8c5e3a36f75f673824f0ae671845292

commit_message:
Changes to section_run_openstack_api_and_schedulers

This patch adds the following minor changes to the
 Run OpenStack API and schedulers section:
"scale-out" to "scale out"
"don't" to "do not"
"That's" to "That is"
"backend" to "back end"

commit_message:
Flexible cells selection.

The aim of this blueprint is to extend filtering capabilities
so that the user can tag his cells and schedule VMs to the cells
which meet the requirements provided in flavor's extra specs.

blueprint flexible-cells-selection
Change-Id: I03fe1631ad8df92e8d3d4e212d813f87d30df358

commit_message:
Display user and project limits

Today the limits API (i.e. nova absolute-limits) only returns
the project limits.  It is useful for the end user to know both
the user and project limits, especially when the end user is
trying to understand how much capacity is used versus how much
capacity is available.

bp user-project-limits

Change-Id: Ie2e4fa294eced7ce1147dbe377e59101af8d99f8

commit_message:
Using cinder volumes backed by VMware raw devices

OpenStack currently lacks support for attaching VMware
raw devices to Virtual machines. This blueprint allows
users to attach and detach cinder volumes backed by
VMware raw devices.

Change-Id: Icc63454cbd38d12442c48b554aba06e7c7034b58
Implements: blueprint vmware-raw-device

commit_message:
Nova trusted geo-asset tag

This spec covers how geo and asset tagging can be incorporated
to OpenStack Nova to provide location and boundary control of
workloads/OpenStack images. With Geo/Asset Tags, you can enforce
policies to control placement, migration or bursting of workloads
to trusted systems in specific geographical locations or boundaries.

Spec for https://blueprints.launchpad.net/openstack/?searchtext=nova-trusted-geo-asset-tag

Change-Id: I3c42769ca808aa3180c2c246e47a1ba145fe6996

commit_message:
Database purge deleted spec

This spec details the ability to cleanly purge 'deleted' rows.
This provides for confirmed data destruction, beyond the current
archive_deleted_rows functionality.

Change-Id: Icd8fa42baa9d9c78677d61b650e6e8c6460e1e84

commit_message:
Add drivertype priority scheduling on migration

In the process of live_migration, if the user does not specify the
destination, the scheduler will choose a suitable host,  but the scheduler
can not choose hosts according to the driver_type and driver_version in
the existing scheduling method, especially in a heterogeneous environment,
it will lead to the migration failure probability increased, so I think
the OpenStack as an excellent choice should be able to deal with this
situation.

Change-Id: I16851fe368a58574b183f5273da7686dd13d64f2

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-24 16:41:54.000000000', 'message': 'Volume affinity based VM placement

Blueprint: volume-affinity-based-vm-placement

Cinder scheduler schedules volume creation on certain host based on scheduler filters in case of multi-node setup. For local volume backends like LVM, the volume resides locally on the host where volume create was scheduled.

For clustered filesystems like IBM General Parallel File System (GPFS) which provides features like FPO (File Placement Optimizer), the volume create command will be run on that host and volume will be created locally if FPO is enabled.

There can be various use cases that leverage the volume locality information, irrespective of cinder backend being used, and instantiate the VM closer to where the volume resides.

Change-Id: I53cc43f854e4004b21838b574221c7d154bdd154

commit_message:
Volume host affinity based VM placement

Blueprint: volume-host-affinity-based-vm-placement

Cinder scheduler schedules volume creation on certain host based on scheduler
filters in case of multi-node setup. For local volume backends like LVM, the
volume resides locally on the host where volume create was scheduled.

There can be various use cases that leverage the volume locality information,
irrespective of cinder backend being used, and instantiate the VM closer to
where the volume resides. Data analytics based on Hadoop and MapReduce is one
of those use cases, which is elaborated in the 'Use Cases' section.

This feature will be useful with any cinder backend which uses local disks to
create a volume. And in case of cinder backends like GPFS, which uses a
clustered filesystem as cinder volume store and in normal case stripes the
volume file across disks available from various nodes in the cluster, this
feature will be useful if such backends support creating volume using disks
available from a particular node only, when indicated so.

Change-Id: I53cc43f854e4004b21838b574221c7d154bdd154

commit_message:
VMware:  Support multi disk images in OVA container format

When OVA support for VMware is added, this spec proposes to follow on with
adding the support for OVA images that contain multiple disk images.

Change-Id: I86330550213ad1d9c7fb7bb5dbc624529cd989e4
Implements: blueprint vmware-driver-ova-multidisk-support

commit_message:
Remove L3 report_state logging

None of the agents log this information, and the reason is that
it's not useful. Any errors are logged, successful state reports
don't give actionable information as you can see that the agent
is up in neutron agent-list anyway.

Change-Id: I109373129808984d34abdf6780b8cda8ca8982be

[{'created': '2015-04-07 13:30:41.000000000', 'message': "Do not re-elect RabbitMQ multistate resource master

Current monitor action for multistate RabbitMQ resource
in Pacemaker  may re-elect existing master when there is
no need to do so. That is a problem as master elections
introduce full cluster downtime and we don't want
additional elections.

The fix is to check whether the given node uptime is equal
to the other nodes uptime and drop this node from the list
of candidates if there is a master exists. Note, there is a
special 'rabbit-master' attribute in CIB for this.

Closes-bug: #1435254

Change-Id: I6f2484fb8f3284f76461c184148d27aa86a5d4b6
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
"}]
commit_message:
Do not re-elect RabbitMQ multistate resource master

Current monitor action for multistate RabbitMQ resource
in Pacemaker  may re-elect existing master when there is
no need to do so. That is a problem as master elections
introduce full cluster downtime and we don't want
additional elections.

The fix is to check whether the given node uptime is equal
to the other nodes uptime and drop this node from the list
of candidates if there is a master exists. Note, there is a
special 'rabbit-master' attribute in CIB for this.

Closes-bug: #1435254

Change-Id: I6f2484fb8f3284f76461c184148d27aa86a5d4b6
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Smarter list_resources for history

This change creates only one query to build the history of
resources, instead of making one query for the latest version,
and another one for the previous versions.

Change-Id: I25c6ac37af5f59150cb37e8f0e89e6e13ad6d541

commit_message:
Reserve 10 migrations for backports

Reserve 10 migrations so that we have the option of backporting fixes
that include a db migration to the stable/kilo branch.  We did this
same thing to allow backports and stable/juno in
c2ce0a90e3155bae77569a285e97f2585f8a964a.

Change-Id: I1e6be551b609d1250f0d9a1078f7c22298686003

commit_message:
Chanages in murano::application_package class

* changes made due to upload mechanism for murano packages has been changed
* this patch-set depends on https://review.fuel-infra.org/#/c/5427/
* removed unused cirros class

Change-Id: I32c69448d06384f3036c5a493db0e744d1770c21
Related-Bug: #1441217
Closes-Bug: #1441274

commit_message:
Fix bond parameters for l23_stored_config provider

* Parameters lacp_rate and xmit_hash_policy are not used in all bond
modes. Hence we do not write them to config file if not necessary.
* Add lacp_rate and xmit_hash_policy support for Ubuntu.

Change-Id: I4ce47af5decc544933936e2031357da6f60b4652
Closes-bug: #1436815

This is certainly more elegant than the current approach, except I did not notice a way to query the bay definitions through an API. Did I miss that part?

I am somewhat concerned about potential confusion between BayModel and Bay Definitions. Is the idea that we would drop Baymodel and replace it with this approach, or that we would have both?'}, {'account_id': 5387, 'date': '2015-03-26 18:20:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

BayDefinitions aren't necessarily a concept we want our API users to have to worry about. They are simply a mapping between the (some what) homogeneous abstraction of Bays and Baymodels and the heterogeneous nature of our Heat templates. Perhaps a better name would be BayTemplateDefinition or TemplateDefinition.

However, BayDefinitions will determine which images, flavors, and COEs can be set in on BayModel. For instance, if an operator has chosen not to enable any BayDefinitions providing a Swarm COE, the users won't be able to create a bay with that COE. We may want to figure out a way to convey that to the user."}, {'account_id': 5387, 'date': '2015-03-26 18:35:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 5387, 'date': '2015-03-26 20:08:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-26 20:14:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add Template Definitions

The idea here is to provide a way for magnum to discover and interact
with templates meant to build bays. Template definition discovery is
done through python entry_points, and each class lists the bay_types
it can provide. Each template definition contains a mapping of magnum
object attributes and heat template parameters/outputs.

This will be useful for not only allowing different CoEs, OSes, and
platforms. But can also provide the discovery mechanism for templates
once they are pulled into their own repository.

Partial-Implements: bp multiple-bay-templates

Change-Id: Ia596657856cd861c94e58dcd65acae0677a36d73

commit_message:
Add 'yum-plugin-priorities' package

Since Fuel 6.1 we are able to work with custom set of repos with custom
priorities. By default, yum is unable to work with them, but it could be
fixed by installing 'yum-plugin-priorities'.

Change-Id: Ic41d306b4899c8ee1830f580418f812539fc22d1
Related-Bug: #1440074

commit_message:
Support for Configuration Language: Puppet

It allows for Puppet as configuration language in the execution plans.
In addition, it creates a base class (ChefPuppetExecutorBase) for
sharing common methods between Puppet and Chef executors.

Change-Id: I65ae656117aa26fc7dff4f83a2be1b4d2c3cb58b

commit_message:
Expand Origin header check for serial console

Serial consoles can use the ws or wss protocols which correspond to http
and https respectively from a security perspective.  The Origin header
check failed has been expanded to allow for those protocols and to match
appropriately with http/https when verifying the protocol security
level.

Change-Id: I7155607488495ba70e6edd550b12abc21b3e69c4
Closes-Bug: 1434611

commit_message:
OVSDB python binding should use row.delete() to remove rows

The OVS python IDL recognize a delete event when delete() is called
on the row, this should be used to remove rows from the db

Change-Id: I50c94a4f089659d78f8881653cd55d4ef069cdc1
Closes-Bug: #1442217

commit_message:
Moving to YAQL 1.0

 * Fixed ProxyAwareDict according to YAQL
   convert data when evaluating expression
 * Fixed expression tests
 * Fixed Engine tests where we refer to unexisting
   variable in context
   (now YAQL raises an error when it doesn't find a
    value using given key)
 * Fixed tests on join (new way to check test correction)

 * YAQL 1.0 has its own builtin functions len() and str
   therefore our ones were deleted.
 * YAQL 1.0 uses '$.where' function instead of '$[$...]'

Implements: blueprint yaql-v1-0

Change-Id: I1b46c4e12aee6f25d1e9ca9daa1da059baf6fb68

commit_message:
Multipath commands with error messages in stdout fail to parse

This change fixes an issue in find_multipath_device() where the command
output of multipath -l <device> would sometimes fail to be parsed if
there were error messages in the stdout string in addition to the
expected output. We will now strip out the error messages before we
attempt to parse the lines.

Change-Id: I3d48debc7d64f6a891ac37d4c2c5ebddfb5b00b0

commit_message:
move setting of novncproxy_base_url

The fixes introduced in order to resolve
https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1409142 (CVE-2015-0259) make
novncproxy_base_url relevant on hosts running the nova-novncproxy
service, whereas previously it was only used by nova-compute to
construct VNC console urls.

This change moves the setting of the novncproxy_base_url option out of
compute.pp and into nova::vncproxy_common, where it can be used both
by compute.pp and vncproxy.pp.

Change-Id: I7af4cf8257f2bdbc7d3cc57930fd6371571db531

commit_message:
Create initiator id if not exist in VMAX driver

This problem was discovered in a customer's environment. If the
initiator id (hardware id SMI-S instance) does not exist on the
array, the attach volume operation will fail. In this patch,
the initiator id will be created if it doesn't exist.

Change-Id: I868118528d831a9f49081a6393e64eb7a414b36f
Closes-Bug: #1440427

commit_message:
Correct wsgi_daemon_process_options key

'owner' is not a valid option for the WSGIDaemonProcess directive. The
correct option is 'user' [1]. Trying to set 'owner' causes the service
to be unable to start. This patch corrects that option name.

[1] https://code.google.com/p/modwsgi/wiki/ConfigurationDirectives#WSGIDaemonProcess

Change-Id: I907fbcb48db823ea8f5caca4496efaaa456ef69c

commit_message:
Fix keystone unit tests

Commit d4073c2 in openstacklib changed the parameters that the keystone
module uses to authenticate. We forgot to update the mocks in the
keystone tests with this change. This patch corrects that mistake.

Change-Id: I9422925984cbc386695fedce950bdb795d7f478d

Hi Sofer, thanks for the patch!

Collector is disabled by default, with this patch we change the default configuration, it's intended ?

We also must provide a way to disable this functionality (I've not tested, but I'm not sure that an empty string into is_ip_valid is valid).

We should add a if/else logic in order to add a ceilometer_config { ensure => absent }, or configure udp_address to an empty string by default and remove ip check."}, {'account_id': 11491, 'date': '2015-03-25 18:24:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Yes! Good catch, Sebastien...'}, {'account_id': 8297, 'date': '2015-03-25 19:27:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Hi, no the service is not disable by default.  It default to "0.0.0.0".  It's only if you explicitly set it to empty that it get disabled:

[root@controller ceilometer]# grep udp_address ceilometer.conf 
#udp_address=0.0.0.0
[root@controller ceilometer]# systemctl restart openstack-ceilometer-collector 
[root@controller ceilometer]# netstat -plaun | grep 4952 
udp        0      0 0.0.0.0:4952            0.0.0.0:*                           10631/python 
[root@controller ceilometer]# vim ceilometer.conf 
[root@controller ceilometer]# systemctl restart openstack-ceilometer-collector
[root@controller ceilometer]# netstat -plaun | grep 4952
[root@controller ceilometer]# grep udp_address ceilometer.conf 
udp_address=

So this doesn't change the default behavior, unless I missed something else ?

Second, I'm quite sure that empty string is not a valid ip, if not, I'll tell them upstream :)  So, now with the validation, we cannot set it to empty.  So, there is now two courses of action:
 - either allow empty to the udp_address and stick to the upstream interface;
 - or add another parameter like "disable_listener"

I tend to prefer the first one, as it's more natural'}, {'account_id': 8297, 'date': '2015-03-25 19:42:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

sorry for the messed up comment.  I try again for the "the listener is not disabled by default" part:

[root@controller ceilometer]# grep udp_address ceilometer.conf 

#udp_address=0.0.0.0

[root@controller ceilometer]# systemctl restart openstack-ceilometer-collector 

[root@controller ceilometer]# netstat -plaun | grep 4952 

udp        0      0 0.0.0.0:4952            0.0.0.0:*                           10631/python 

[root@controller ceilometer]# vim ceilometer.conf 

[root@controller ceilometer]# grep udp_address ceilometer.conf 
udp_address=

[root@controller ceilometer]# systemctl restart openstack-ceilometer-collector

[root@controller ceilometer]# netstat -plaun | grep 4952

Hope it clarifies the matter.  I'm uploading a patch right now that implement the udp_address interface fully and still keep the ip validation part.  I added another test as I went, like this all the paths are tested.'}, {'account_id': 8297, 'date': '2015-03-25 19:44:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 8297, 'date': '2015-03-25 19:56:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 8297, 'date': '2015-03-25 20:00:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 11491, 'date': '2015-03-25 20:00:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 11491, 'date': '2015-03-25 20:10:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-25 20:20:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Verified-1

- gate-murano-devstack-dsvm http://logs.openstack.org/65/125565/1/check/gate-murano-devstack-dsvm/a420211 : SUCCESS in 15m 51s'}, {'account_id': 8040, 'date': '2014-10-02 09:36:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 8040, 'date': '2014-10-02 09:43:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

Thomas, I'm glad muranodashboard finally has been packaged, but I'm a bit concerned by the fact that there is no particular version specified for django-nose in global reqs: https://github.com/openstack/requirements/blob/master/global-requirements.txt#L175 

We either need to convince OpenStack folks to update the requirement for django-nose, or restrict django-nose to >=1.2 somewhere in deb-package."}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2014-10-02 14:23:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

My Debian package already build-depends on python-django-nose (>= 1.2), that's not the issue. The issue is that your test-requirements.txt can't just lie and pretend it supports any version of django-nose when this is not the reality. As I wrote on IRC, there's 2 solutions:

1/ Fix global-requirements.txt to use django-nose>=1.2
2/ Fix murano-dashboard so that it works with 1.1

The 2nd option would be more work, but it wont be a problem with anyone. It is to be noted by the way that even Trusty has django-nose 1.2, so it shouldn't be a problem. Only RedHat is a concern. How can I check for their version?"}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2014-10-02 14:27:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I've asked for a freeze exception:

https://review.openstack.org/125651

lets see how it turns out."}, {'account_id': 7225, 'date': '2015-03-16 09:31:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2 Workflow-1

Blocking this change due to soon to be declared Feature Freeze'}, {'account_id': 7549, 'date': '2015-04-10 07:42:05.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Fixed django-nose requirement

murano-dashboard tests are just completely failing when
using django-nose 1.1, with the below error:

OptionConflictError: option -p/--pattern:
    conflicting option string(s): -p

This patch imposes Django>=1.2 to reflect the current reality.

Change-Id: Ic98f52be11cad629b9f2b567a65c1c36d27abbbb

commit_message:
Fixed regression in the RPC module

Code related to RPC that was moved from the API application to the
global RPC module used an invalid type for the version (float instead of
string).

Change-Id: I0f06cc6324065926b8db05d0015a4a689700c557

commit_message:
Make cells Response de/serialize objects

Currently, cells messaging Response lacks the ability to serialize and
deserialize objects. This change adds support so that message methods
in cells/messaging.py are enabled to respond with objects.

Closes-Bug: #1438514

Change-Id: Ie87167bc1cce25e25ffad2214dfe3c78ef830561

commit_message:
Set line-height for search-icons

Before, to set correct height of search icons 'top' property of
form-control-feedback class was overriden from default horizon value of
0. This caused other icons in dynamic-ui be incorrectly positioned.

This commit sets line-height for search icons to center the
search icons and not alter any other value.

Change-Id: Ie65a9d4e896be6558fb1137565c2d0afeb720d24
Closes-Bug: #1439024

commit_message:
Stacktrace on live migration monitoring

If we catch a error during the live migration monitoring we should
stacktrace since this is an unexpected error.

Just add exc_info in order to not change the translated string since we
are in a string freeze.

Change-Id: I75dacb49b1f2881b6030e0e1ac3e577debc4942c
Related-Bug: #1438803

commit_message:
Use new location for atomic images

I applied for a proper group name for Magnum with fedora.  See
infrastructure ticket:

    https://fedorahosted.org/fedora-infrastructure/ticket/4717

This allows serving files from:

    https://fedorapeople.org/groups/magnum/

Closes-Bug: #1442450

Change devtack and documentation accordingly.

Change-Id: I37b005bc50b8045d47c99085ddf8b6b7196a3fa2

commit_message:
Adding log messages to improve error handling

This patch adds log messages, where raised errors
do not propagate to user during resolve build in
functions get_param and get_attr.

Change-Id: I5409f9f9b6542f28b1b5873092ef607949cbc58d
Closes-Bug: #1346968

commit_message:
Get members from DB when deleting loadbalancer

When the Load Balancer members are created as a result of autoscaling
groups update or adjust, the reference to the current members is
stored in the database and not in the template. so heat will miss some
members when delete loadbalancer.

Change-Id: Ibcd763b3d73f91b3c09bcf3b5e3162fcf100c3d0
Closes-Bug: #1310602

commit_message:
Add --preview option to stack abandon command

Option --preview is used to get abandon data without deleting the
stack. It's very useful to perform dry run abandon before stack update
to get a copy of healthy data for later adopt if update failure found.

Partical-Bug: #1300830

commit_message:
Implements neutron group based policy resources

This is the first in a series of patches which implement
resources for neutron group policy APIs.

This patch implements four new resources:
 - Endpoint
 - EndpointGroup
 - L2-Policy
 - L3-Policy

Implements: blueprint neutron-grouppolicy

Change-Id: Ifa7372c3a1fefadafb74718ea3ff1c48c0d48c4b

commit_message:
Group policy API-2 resources: Classifiers, Actions and Rules

This is the second patch in the Group Policy resources implementation
series. This patch implements:
Policy Classifiers
Policy Actions
Policy Rules

In the context of larger Group Policy model, the Policy Rule resource
is referenced by Contracts, which will be introduced in the subsequent
patch.

Change-Id: Iaff15a534f7ac6b979c8b783907705406ee2cbb2
Implements: blueprint neutron-grouppolicy

commit_message:
Group Policy API-3: Contracts

This is the third patch in the Group Policy resources implementation
series. This patch implements:
Contracts

In the context of larger Group Policy model, Contracts contain Policy
Rules and Endpoint Groups consume or provide Contracts.

Change-Id: If12f966ac360d2dd9f459d720fc4114e7ffc6e9e
Implements: blueprint neutron-grouppolicy

commit_message:
validate a invalid number_typed parameter

if input a invalid string (i.e.'aaaa') to a number type parameter
heat will raise a ERROR but create the stack sucessfully.
Because other operations like stack-list will parse existing stack again,
these operations will fail and lead strange behavior to heat user.

Change-Id: Ifbf266a595a0cbe1f8f4990757ca83a456f2b997
Closes-bug: #1321549

If a custom auth_encryption_key is set, and the custom
key is less than 32 chars, the encryption/decryption

to 32 chars. Add tests.

Change-Id: I6c461416d9889165af0eb003e5903bc188156464
'}]
commit_message:
Require at least 8 chars for auth_encryption_key

If a custom auth_encryption_key is set, and the custom
key is less than 32 chars, the encryption/decryption
fails with a trace. We can however easily pad it
to 32 chars. Add tests.

Change-Id: I6c461416d9889165af0eb003e5903bc188156464

But with your json file as input, it do not work as expected, output yaml doesn't contain quotas(64: F17-x86_64-cfntools) ,it's weird.

},

and the template that you have mentioned has the values in same line i.e.

"F17": { "32" : "F17-i386-cfntools", "64" : "F17-x86_64-cfntools" },

This different is causing the change of 32 to '32'.

commit_message:
Adds multi-cloud to OS::Heat::Stack resource

Adds more properties you can specify in context
to allow creating stack resource in other cloud.
Added properties:
* username
* password
* tenant_name
* auth_url

Change-Id: Ibe35d0b92d523449416a7db8afcf7e96bf593341
Implements: blueprint multi-region-support

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster

commit_message:
Title:Heat to assert the states of the server

Heat today does not assert the state of the Server that is provisioned from the Heat template. I propose Heat to assert the states of the server in order to be able to update or add to the configuration of the heat template at any given point of time and from/to any state of the Server

Change-Id: I7fbe6d773e8ea01fb819692f0ff587783cd7192d

commit_message:
Kubernetes pod resources for container management

A config and deployment resource to support kubernetes(k8s) pods
(a colocated group of 'docker' containers with shared
volumes).

Specifies: bp k8s-container-pod-resources

commit_message:
Encryption/decryption of sections in a HOT template.

For security, licensing and other reasons it is desirable
to have encryption capability enabling free exchange of HOT
sections while still ensuring that only the intended parties
can use them.

Change-Id: Ib5b7ebc56f1c69bcd282cc5831599bd818972b8b

None of this belongs in Heat. Implementing it in Heat makes exactly as much sense as doing it in Horizon - both are interfaces to public APIs. They are *certainly* not going to go behind Nova's back and mess with the hypervisor."}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2014-09-26 03:02:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I'd love to encourage HA in any way possible, but as Zane says much of this belongs elsewhere. Some of it should be as Heat resources. First you need sensible actions in nova (restarting, and keeping networks etc...) you need to worry about the interactions between resources when actioning recovery. Then you could introduce an HA policy resource that could respond to ceilometer alarms. This policy resource would then call the underlying actions on resources to recover. HArestarter is really a policy resource, but it fails as it does not work well with the rest of the stack's resources and the resources that are dependant on the resource been "restarted/re-created". Perhaps the unit of recovery needs to be a nested stack to get around this (a bit like how the autoscaling works). Basically recovery is not always simple, and recovery can get messy.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-06 22:26:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Automatically pull all element READMEs into docs

This adds a tiny sphinx extension that runs a shell script that copies
(with modifications) each element's README.rst into the doc tree.

The elements symlink is deleted; this is no longer required, as the
directory is recreated each time the docs job is run.

Change-Id: I1d2c6b5021cdeb00eb6e3a13c8a56d5b7ee94154

commit_message:
Add a vlan check

Adds a vlan check job for TripleO

This is intended to be used for testing new public-IP functionality.

This patchset partially completes a spec which will one day live at
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/tripleo/+specs/tripleo-juno-virtual-public-ips
but for now can bee seen in  Id9addc65f0d2ed519ce4b3edbd561ed660a2786e.

The details of the public VIP - including vlan tags, interface names,
network ranges and so on - are assumed to be provided in $TE_DATAFILE
but not activated by default.

Change-Id: I0f9e4cd4dfca3e7baae747255bc84e6efd52bcd2
Requires: I231c0aaff787c8dd88f50587b6a5cdf9c9e63b0f
Requires: I78c0fa3902c1e480b7ada0055332b14828c3c7f9

commit_message:
No need to create APIVersionRequest every time

APIVersionRequest will be created everytime when the microversion
is used. Actually we can create them once and used later.

Change-Id: I5d62003b87b85bc5020fe32788d255bc7273a9c9

commit_message:
auth_encryption_key is being checked to be 16, 24, or 32

If auth_encryption_key length is not 16 or 24 or 32 in that case
heat operations such as stack-creates fails. This check has been
added.

Change-Id: Ic653d18dbb7523ca5286ae0951eb86ad72cbdb13
Closes-bug: #1415887

commit_message:
Add a "show_hidden" parameter to stack-list API

Passing "show_hidden=True" will result in hidden stacks being shown in
the stack listing.

blueprint stack-tags

Change-Id: I3074282131443c8e3894f9ce9e363a4438f5a11e

commit_message:
Add ability to hide stacks based on tag

Add a "hidden_stack_tags" option that contains a list of tag names.
Stacks that have one or more of these tags will be hidden.

Add an option to show hidden stacks in the stack listing.

blueprint stack-tags

Change-Id: I45a5ac6d73a9a61629a56f88270e3a97fafb378a

commit_message:
[Launch Instance Fix] Add Configuration Step Unit Tests

This patch adds unit tests for the configuration step.  These tests are focused
around the controller and its related components (no selenium tests or view
tests).

Co-Authored-By: Brian Tully <brian.tully@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Shaoquan Chen <sean.chen2@hp.com>
Change-Id: Ic25a36ca598459cce4a577da0a99175fbcd1d27a
Partial-Bug: 1435869

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-25 13:46:40.000000000', 'message': 'Prevent using required=True with default value

The current schema of constraints allow to use default values for
required=True. However we never use it except in unittests, because
resource property with required=True should be specified anyway and
default value will be redundant in this case. This patch fixes it in all
tests and adds checking for constraint schema class.

Change-Id: Ic6ace30742e887069f119a14ffb091f6bac9e682
'}, {'created': '2014-08-25 16:47:32.000000000', 'message': 'Prevent using required=True with default value

The current schema of constraints allow to use default values for
required=True. However we never use it except in unittests and one
resource in contrib directory, because resource property with
required=True should be specified anyway and default value will be
redundant in this case. This patch fixes it in all tests and adds
checking for constraint schema class.

Change-Id: Ic6ace30742e887069f119a14ffb091f6bac9e682
'}, {'created': '2015-03-31 12:19:39.000000000', 'message': 'Deprecate using required=True with default value

The current schema of constraints allow to use default values for
required=True. However we never use it except in unittests, because
user should set it always, which looks like not required property.
This patch adds checking for constraint schema class with warning

commit_message:
Deprecate using required=True with default value

The current schema of constraints allow to use default values for
required=True. However we never use it except in unittests, because
user should set it always, which looks like not required property.
This patch adds checking for constraint schema class with warning
message.

Change-Id: Ic6ace30742e887069f119a14ffb091f6bac9e682

I did a quick search through the code and found only one property that has both required and default. This is the "config_actions" property of the OS::Heat::SoftwareComponent resource.

Kairat, have you found more properties?

I think this warning has two problems:
- the word "deprecate" suggests it is the property that will be deprecated, not its default value, as Qiming noted.
- the warning makes the assumption that properties that have required and default set must have their default value removed. But this may not always be true, maybe the required value was included by mistake, such as a copy/paste error.'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-03-24 19:11:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I submitted a separate proposal that addresses the property in SoftwareComponent: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/167365/. For this specific case, my opinion is that it is safe to just remove the default values.

commit_message:
Make disk property of flavor default

DISK property of NovaFlavor resource is ambiguous: it is required
and it has default value. The property has been changed to
default only (to support compatibility and not break
existing templates). In addition, added test that check resources
about amibigious property definition.

Change-Id: I51be18b7201e78d6af261f678ddf440aa0fa893e
Closes-bug: #1436331

commit_message:
Fix a issue for kafka-publisher and refactor the test code

Fix a issue which causes error when default policy is selected.
Add test codes to avoid the same mistakes again.
Fix a bug of the test code which is:
* KafkaBrokerPublisher tries to connect localhost when __init__
  is called because of the lack of mocking _get_client function
  before initializing KafkaBrokerPublisher.

Closes-Bug: 1441175
Closes-Bug: 1441258
Change-Id: I306db443a866860ee45b2362b8a0cd2a59d8c3a2

Add comma missing from list of data source drivers

Missing comma from devstack script is making congress erroneously import a
module named IronicDrivercongress.tests.fake_datasource.

commit_message:
Fix here-document usage

Use tabs instead of whitespace to indent lines of the here-document. Tabs
indent the text properly in the shell script and are omitted from the output.
Otherwise, running the shell script produces this error:

./prepare_devstack.sh: line 30: warning: here-document at line 21 delimited by
end-of-file (wanted `EOF')
./prepare_devstack.sh: line 31: syntax error: unexpected end of file

Change-Id: I893cd43dfbebd751b0ad5fb3ffff188c40fc862e

commit_message:
Create policy via Horizon

* congress.py: New API function to create a policy.

policies/
* forms.py: Form to create a policy.
* tables.py: Move code for listing a policy's rules in a table to a new module,
  keeping the rules code separate. Add new button to create a policy.

policies/rules/
* __init__.py: Separate out rules code into its own module.
* tables.py: Moved rules code from policies/table.py to here.
* urls.py: Add new url for policy creation.
* views.py: Add new view for policy creation. Get PolicyRulesTable from new
  rules module. Add more logging.

policies/templates/policies/
* _create.html: Form to create a new policy.
* create.html: Contains modal form to create a new policy.
* policies_table.html, policy_rules_table.html: Remove unused templates.

Partially implements blueprint: horizon-create-policies

Change-Id: I93337d0d47a94c13960a7fa69aa97edec8615f9b

Paste it here - no idea how to publish comment for old patchset:-(

Current deepsix.publish() only accepts newdata and it replaces pubdata[dataindex].dataObj with newdata, then it calls push(). At this point, we lost the old data. In push(), the saved newdata is passed down into prepush_processor(), I think it's just used for 'sub' type msg, i.e. giving a new subscriber the current data. For 'pub' msg, for example, datasource driver will grap delta from its own states:

978 # grab deltas

979 to_add = self.state_set_diff(self.state, self.prior_state, dataindex)

980 to_del = self.state_set_diff(self.prior_state, self.state, dataindex)

So, currently it's convenient to save the delta in policySubData, just like the datasource driver's state and prior_state."}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2015-04-01 17:05:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
publish policy table result to dse bus

This patch implements subscriptions for the policy engine. That is,
every time someone subscribes to a policy engine table, the policy
engine will publish the results of that table on the message bus.

Implements blueprint: publish-policy-results-to-bus

Change-Id: I8161d233e64a9bff5d4fa31c02b368a5ef75c878

commit_message:
Honor uuid parameter passed to nova-network create

The nova api for creating nova-network networks has an optional
request parameter "id" which maps to the string uuid for the
network to create. The nova-manage network create command represents
it as the option --uuid. The parameter is currently being ignored
by the nova-network manager. This change sets the uuid when creating
the network if it has been specified.

Closes-Bug: #1441931

Change-Id: Ib29e632b09905f557a7a6910d58207ed91cdc047

commit_message:
Refactor nova-net cidr validation in prep for bug fix

The network manager create_networks function is on the verge of the
"too complex" pep8 check error, so this change refactors the cidr
validation code out into a private function in preparation for
fixing a bug.

Change-Id: Id0603ddd642acccfa12ae53a52ecfb66dca53702

Hi Jay, I see your point. And maybe my desire to move this into Template.validate() was too idealistic. So this won't be a show-stopper.

I am adding Zane to the review; he had some pretty good ideas several times in the past.

@Zane: any opinion on this?"}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-05-19 23:14:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

OK, so the missing analysis here is that validation of the version only occurs in template_format.parse(), and that only happens when the template is initially converted from YAML, which in most cases is in the client?

I'd prefer to do the validation on the heat-engine side (already this is leaving out heat-cfn-api by the looks of it) for a number of reasons. The fact that we're still hard-coding legit versions here is a bit of a hack, given that the engine can now handle pluggable parsers. So I'd prefer some code in the engine that validates the version against the available plugins.

Of course the plugin loading code does that already, except that it has a default to deal with the thousands of unit tests that don't include a version :( So unless some kind/brave soul wants to fix that I guess it will be a bit messy for now.

Is validate_template the only call affected? It seems like create/update must have the same problem."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-19 23:14:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

[{'created': '2015-04-07 07:29:31.000000000', 'message': "Remove EC2 test case that incompatible with Amazon

This test tries to allocate address and disassociate it without association.
Amazon allows to do it for EC2-classic and does not throw error.
But EC2 implementation in Nova throws error.
We have the same test in our own test suite against stackforge/ec2-api
(but it's not merged yet) and I checked it against Amazon -
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171050/

I suggest to remove this test from tempest as incompatible with Amazon.
Also because of EC2 is deprecated in nova and can't be fixed.

Change-Id: I711314408ec7c4ea75f93348a7335843713e9a2b
"}]
commit_message:
Remove EC2 test case that incompatible with Amazon

This test tries to allocate address and disassociate it without association.
Amazon allows to do it for EC2-classic and does not throw error.
But EC2 implementation in Nova throws error.
We have the same test in our own test suite against stackforge/ec2-api
(but it's not merged yet) and I checked it against Amazon -
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171050/

I suggest to remove this test from tempest as incompatible with Amazon.
Also because of EC2 is deprecated in nova and can't be fixed.

Change-Id: I711314408ec7c4ea75f93348a7335843713e9a2b

commit_message:
accept languagepack name or uuid when prompting during 'app create'

During 'app create', we list and prompt for a languagepack if one
is not given using the --lp flag or in the planfile.

At this point, we only accept LP names, we should accept uuids as
well, just like in the planfile.

Change-Id: I9ebeb056475bcb46158d83e3dfd9ab1c339c5d38
Closes-bug: 1441886

commit_message:
Libvirt: preallocate_images CONFIG can be arbitrary characters

We can now set preallocate_images as any characters as long as it is
not equal to 'none' to enable preallocate images function, this is
too bad.

This patch changes the condition to equal to 'space'/'Space'/'SPACE'

Closes-Bug: 1427092
Change-Id: Ie8f4861fb77d2c3c3a8976fb7768ced12e7d8d5b

commit_message:
Agent driver fails without Ironic-managed TFTP

There are a lot of assumptions that Ironic has local PXE files.
This is untrue for deployments with separate DHCP servers and
agent images not hosted in Glance. Adds a new config option
'manage_tftp' in the DCHP section to disable TFTP management.

Closes-Bug: #1440896
Change-Id: Ibf5a415e3beee13d12e65e177816256df57cb423

commit_message:
use keystone v3 api to fetch revocation list

Currently, keystone v2.0 url is hardcoded to fetch revocation list.
However, we should chose the corresponding api according to the value
of auth_version.

Change-Id: I2cf97eadfd6e410b89d8ba50f81de2fa7ec68db9
Closes-Bug: #1379506

commit_message:
Move reseller spec for Liberty release

We already have implemented the following features:

- A new field will be added to the project table to represent if that
  project has the domain feature;
- Update the domain operations to execute in the project table
- Allow create subdomain using a parent_id
- Migrate the domains for project table
- Drop domain table

Now in liberty release we want work to approve this features.

The other features mentioned in this spec will not be implemeted since
we need to discuss better in the next summit, there is:

- Migrate the role assignments for DomainUser and DomainGroups types.
- Provide dual scoped token for a project with domain feature

previously-approved: kilo

Change-Id: If357f38a8d81b094f47cd1a055dbec7edfb945ae
Implements: bp reseller

commit_message:
move tasks to after the dictionary updates

The tasks added to the task table needs to have the latest
info after all of the updates to the data. This fix ensures that
is the case for a few places that where missed.

Change-Id: I58abe55a5fab54f038637398455855c140141622
Signed-off-by: Joe Mills <joe@midokura.com>
